const QUESTIONS = [
{id:1,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the correct compression-to-breath ratio for adult CPR performed by a single rescuer?",o:["30 compressions to 2 breaths","15 compressions to 1 breath","20 compressions to 2 breaths","15 compressions to 2 breaths","10 compressions to 2 breaths"],a:0,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"The American Heart Association recommends a 30:2 compression-to-ventilation ratio for single-rescuer adult CPR."},
{id:2,cat:"first-aid",q:"At what depth should chest compressions be performed on an adult during CPR?",o:["About 1 inch, enough for shallow effect","About 3 inches deep into the chest","At least 2 inches but no more than 2.4","About 4 inches for maximum compression","About 0.5 inches with gentle pressure"],a:2,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"AHA guidelines specify chest compressions should be at least 2 inches deep but no more than 2.4 inches for adults."},
{id:3,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the recommended rate of chest compressions during CPR?",o:["60 to 80 compressions per minute","80 to 100 compressions per minute","50 to 70 compressions per minute","120 to 140 compressions per minute","100 to 120 compressions per minute"],a:4,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"The AHA recommends a compression rate of 100 to 120 per minute for effective CPR."},
{id:4,cat:"first-aid",q:"When using an AED, what should you do immediately before delivering a shock?",o:["Apply firm pressure to the patient's chest","Ensure no one is touching the patient at all","Give the patient two full rescue breaths","Check for a pulse at the carotid artery","Remove the pads and reposition them carefully"],a:1,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"Before pressing the shock button on an AED, ensure no one is touching the patient to prevent injury from the electrical current."},
{id:5,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the first step in the adult Chain of Survival for out-of-hospital cardiac arrest?",o:["Begin CPR with chest compressions immediately","Use an AED as soon as one is available","Check for normal breathing and responsiveness","Call 911 or activate emergency medical services","Administer epinephrine as the first intervention"],a:3,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"The first link in the Chain of Survival is early recognition and activation of the emergency response system by calling 911."},
{id:6,cat:"first-aid",q:"For an unresponsive adult who is not breathing normally, what should a trained bystander do first?",o:["Call 911 and then begin CPR right away","Place the person into the recovery position","Begin providing rescue breathing only first","Drive them to the nearest hospital quickly","Wait for EMS to arrive before taking action"],a:0,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"A trained bystander should call 911 (or have someone call) and immediately begin CPR for an unresponsive adult who is not breathing normally."},
{id:7,cat:"first-aid",q:"Hands-only CPR is recommended for which situation?",o:["Drowning victims who are found unresponsive","Infants who are under 1 year of age","Untrained bystanders witnessing adult sudden collapse","Choking victims who are still fully conscious","Drug overdose victims who are still breathing"],a:2,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"Hands-only CPR (compressions without rescue breaths) is recommended for untrained bystanders who witness an adult suddenly collapse."},
{id:8,cat:"first-aid",q:"Where should AED pads be placed on an adult?",o:["Both pads placed on the left side of the chest","One pad on the forehead and one on the chest","One pad placed on each of the shoulder blades","Both pads centered on the upper back region","Upper right chest and lower left side of the ribs"],a:4,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"Standard AED pad placement is one pad on the upper right chest below the collarbone and one on the lower left side below the armpit."},
{id:9,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the universal sign for choking?",o:["Waving both arms frantically above the head","Clutching the throat with one or both hands","Pointing repeatedly toward the mouth area","Stomping both feet hard on the ground","Covering the entire face with both hands firmly"],a:1,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"The universal sign for choking is clutching the throat with one or both hands, indicating the person cannot breathe."},
{id:10,cat:"first-aid",q:"How many abdominal thrusts should you give before rechecking a choking adult's airway?",o:["Give exactly 3 thrusts and then recheck the airway","Give exactly 5 thrusts and then recheck the airway","Give exactly 10 thrusts and then recheck the airway","Continue until the object is expelled or person goes unconscious","Give exactly 1 strong thrust and then recheck the airway"],a:3,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Continue cycles of 5 back blows and 5 abdominal thrusts until the object is dislodged or the person becomes unresponsive, then begin CPR."},
{id:11,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the correct hand placement for abdominal thrusts (Heimlich maneuver) on a conscious choking adult?",o:["Just above the belly button, below the breastbone","On the center of the chest over the sternum area","On the lower back right between the shoulder blades","On the upper chest area just below the throat","On the stomach area well below the belly button"],a:0,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Place the thumb side of your fist just above the navel and well below the breastbone, then grasp with the other hand and thrust inward and upward."},
{id:12,cat:"first-aid",q:"For a choking infant under 1 year old, what technique is recommended?",o:["Abdominal thrusts delivered while seated upright","Finger sweeps to clear the airway path manually","Alternating 5 back blows and 5 chest thrusts","The standard Heimlich maneuver performed from behind","Encouraging them to cough the object out forcefully"],a:2,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"For infants under 1 year, alternate 5 back blows (between the shoulder blades) and 5 chest thrusts. Do not perform abdominal thrusts on infants."},
{id:13,cat:"first-aid",q:"If a choking person becomes unconscious, what should you do?",o:["Continue performing abdominal thrusts on the ground","Wait for EMS while closely monitoring their breathing","Perform a blind finger sweep inside the mouth","Tilt them upside down to dislodge the stuck object","Lower them to the ground and then begin CPR"],a:4,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"If a choking person becomes unconscious, carefully lower them to the ground, call 911 if not already done, and begin CPR. Look in the mouth before giving breaths."},
{id:14,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the preferred method to control severe external bleeding?",o:["Apply a tourniquet to the injured limb immediately","Apply direct pressure using a clean cloth or bandage","Elevate the injured limb well above the heart level","Pour cold water directly on the wound to slow flow","Apply a loose bandage and wait for professional help"],a:1,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Direct pressure with a clean cloth or bandage is the first and most effective method to control severe external bleeding."},
{id:15,cat:"first-aid",q:"When should a tourniquet be applied to control bleeding?",o:["For any cut or wound that is bleeding actively","Only by licensed medical professionals in a hospital","Only on fingers and toes where direct pressure fails","When direct pressure fails to control life-threatening limb bleeding","Never under any circumstances as they are too dangerous"],a:3,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"A tourniquet should be applied when direct pressure cannot control life-threatening bleeding from a limb. Modern guidelines support trained bystander use."},
{id:16,cat:"first-aid",q:"Where should a tourniquet be placed on a bleeding limb?",o:["2 to 3 inches above the wound, toward the heart","On a joint such as the elbow or the knee area","Directly over the wound itself to stop the bleeding","Below the wound on the side away from the heart","At the wrist or ankle near the end of the extremity"],a:0,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Place the tourniquet 2 to 3 inches above the wound, between the wound and the heart, and not on a joint."},
{id:17,cat:"first-aid",q:"What does the acronym RICE stand for in first aid for sprains and strains?",o:["Rest, Immobilize, Clean, Examine","Run, Ice, Cover, Elevate carefully","Rest, Ice, Compression, Elevation","Recover, Ice, Compress, Exercise","Rest, Irrigate, Compress, Evaluate"],a:2,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"RICE stands for Rest, Ice, Compression, and Elevation, a standard first aid protocol for soft tissue injuries."},
{id:18,cat:"first-aid",q:"What type of bleeding is characterized by bright red blood that spurts with each heartbeat?",o:["Venous bleeding from a damaged vein wall","Capillary bleeding from the skin surface area","Superficial bleeding from minor skin abrasions","Internal bleeding from damaged organ tissue","Arterial bleeding from a damaged artery wall"],a:4,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Arterial bleeding produces bright red blood that spurts in rhythm with the heartbeat and is the most serious type of external bleeding."},
{id:19,cat:"first-aid",q:"How long should you apply direct pressure to a wound before checking if bleeding has stopped?",o:["About 30 seconds of steady firm pressure","At least 10 to 15 minutes of steady pressure","About 2 minutes of steady consistent pressure","About 5 seconds of steady firm pressure applied","About 1 minute of steady consistent pressure"],a:1,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Apply steady direct pressure for at least 10 to 15 minutes without lifting the bandage to check, as this can disrupt clot formation."},
{id:20,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the primary danger of a nosebleed that won't stop after 20 minutes of proper first aid?",o:["A bacterial infection developing in the nasal cavity","A previously undetected fracture of the nose bone","A concussion or other serious underlying head injury","A posterior nosebleed requiring prompt medical attention","An allergic reaction causing the prolonged bleeding"],a:3,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"A nosebleed lasting more than 20 minutes despite proper first aid may indicate a posterior nosebleed, which can be serious and requires medical attention."},
{id:21,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the correct first aid for a minor burn (first-degree)?",o:["Run cool water over the burn for at least 10 minutes","Apply butter or cooking oil to soothe the burned area","Apply ice directly to the burn for immediate relief","Pop any blisters that form to help release the pressure","Cover the burn tightly using adhesive tape and gauze"],a:0,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Cool running water for at least 10 minutes is the recommended first aid for minor burns. Never apply ice, butter, or oil."},
{id:22,cat:"first-aid",q:"Which burn severity involves damage to all layers of the skin and possibly underlying tissue?",o:["First-degree burn affecting only the outer layer","Second-degree burn affecting the top two layers","Third-degree burn affecting all layers of skin","Superficial burn affecting only the skin surface","Minor burn causing only temporary redness"],a:2,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Third-degree (full-thickness) burns damage all layers of the skin and may affect underlying fat, muscle, or bone."},
{id:23,cat:"first-aid",q:"What should you NOT do when treating a severe burn?",o:["Call 911 for immediate emergency medical assistance","Cover the burn with a sterile non-stick dressing","Monitor the victim carefully for early signs of shock","Cool the burn area with clean cool running water","Remove any clothing that is stuck to the burn"],a:4,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Never try to remove clothing that is stuck to a burn, as this can cause further tissue damage. Cut around stuck clothing instead."},
{id:24,cat:"first-aid",q:"How can you tell the difference between a second-degree and a first-degree burn?",o:["Second-degree burns are always completely painless","Second-degree burns characteristically produce blisters","First-degree burns always turn the skin white or gray","Second-degree burns affect only the outer skin layer","There is no visible difference between the two types"],a:1,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Second-degree (partial-thickness) burns characteristically produce blisters, while first-degree burns cause only redness and pain without blistering."},
{id:25,cat:"first-aid",q:"For a chemical burn to the skin, what is the recommended first aid?",o:["Apply a neutralizing chemical agent to the area","Cover the area with a dry sterile cloth right away","Apply a thick layer of petroleum jelly for protection","Brush off dry chemical then flush with cool water","Apply antibiotic ointment and a bandage over the area"],a:3,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Brush off any dry chemical first, then flush the area with large amounts of cool running water for at least 20 minutes. Do not try to neutralize chemicals."},
{id:26,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the primary sign of a closed fracture?",o:["Pain, swelling, and deformity without a skin break","A visible open wound present at the injury site","Bone visibly protruding through the broken skin area","No pain or any discomfort felt at the injury site","Only numbness and tingling in the affected limb area"],a:0,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"A closed fracture presents with pain, swelling, and possible deformity, but the skin remains intact with no bone protruding."},
{id:27,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the first aid principle for a suspected fracture?",o:["Attempt to carefully realign the broken bone ends","Apply heat directly to the injury to reduce swelling","Immobilize it in position found, then seek medical care","Have the person walk on it to test if it is broken","Massage the injured area gently to improve blood flow"],a:2,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Immobilize the injury in the position found, apply ice to reduce swelling, and seek professional medical care. Never attempt to realign a bone."},
{id:28,cat:"first-aid",q:"When splinting a suspected fracture, what areas should the splint immobilize?",o:["Only the area at the immediate break site","Only the single joint directly below the fracture","Only the single joint directly above the fracture","The entire limb from the torso to the fingertips","The joints both above and below the fracture site"],a:4,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"A splint should immobilize the joints above and below the suspected fracture to prevent movement at the break site."},
{id:29,cat:"first-aid",q:"Which of the following is a sign of shock?",o:["Flushed, warm, and dry skin throughout the body","Pale or grayish, cool, and clammy feeling skin","A slow, strong, and bounding peripheral pulse","Consistently high blood pressure reading on check","An increased appetite and a strong sense of thirst"],a:1,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Signs of shock include pale or grayish, cool, and clammy skin, rapid weak pulse, rapid breathing, confusion, and weakness."},
{id:30,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the correct position for a person showing signs of shock (without head, neck, or back injury)?",o:["Seated fully upright in a sturdy supportive chair","Lying face down flat on their stomach surface","Standing upright and walking around slowly nearby","Lying flat with their legs elevated about 12 inches","Sitting with their head placed between their knees"],a:3,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Lay the person flat on their back and elevate the legs about 12 inches to help blood flow to vital organs, unless contraindicated by other injuries."},
{id:31,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the most important thing to do while waiting for EMS when someone is in shock?",o:["Keep them warm with a blanket, monitor breathing","Give them plenty of water or fruit juice to drink","Perform continuous chest compressions on the person","Apply cold packs to the forehead and the neck area","Have them sit up and take slow deep calming breaths"],a:0,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Keep the person warm by covering them with a blanket, do not give them anything to eat or drink, and continuously monitor their breathing and consciousness."},
{id:32,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the normal body temperature range for a healthy adult?",o:["95.0°F to 96.5°F (35.0°C to 35.8°C)","100.0°F to 101.0°F (37.8°C to 38.3°C)","97.8°F to 99.1°F, about 98.6°F (37°C)","94.0°F to 95.0°F (34.4°C to 35.0°C)","101.0°F to 102.0°F (38.3°C to 38.9°C)"],a:2,src:"CDC",exp:"Normal body temperature for a healthy adult is approximately 98.6°F (37°C), with a typical range of about 97.8°F to 99.1°F."},
{id:33,cat:"first-aid",q:"At what core body temperature is hypothermia generally considered to begin?",o:["At 98.6°F (37°C), which is normal temperature","At 96.0°F (35.6°C), which is slightly below normal","At 90°F (32.2°C), the moderate hypothermia range","At 100°F (37.8°C), which is slightly above normal","Below 95°F (35°C), which is clinically hypothermic"],a:4,src:"CDC",exp:"Hypothermia is generally defined as a core body temperature below 95°F (35°C). It can be life-threatening and requires immediate attention."},
{id:34,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the recommended first aid for mild hypothermia?",o:["Immerse the person in very hot water right away","Move to warmth, remove wet clothes, warm the core","Rub the person's arms and legs vigorously to warm","Give the person alcohol to warm them up internally","Have them exercise vigorously to generate body heat"],a:1,src:"CDC",exp:"Move the person to a warm place, remove wet clothing, and warm the center of the body (chest, neck, head, groin) first using blankets or skin-to-skin contact."},
{id:35,cat:"first-aid",q:"Why should you NOT give alcohol to a hypothermia victim?",o:["It has absolutely no effect on their body temperature","It raises the core body temperature far too quickly","It makes the person much too alert and very restless","It dilates blood vessels and increases overall heat loss","It causes only mild dehydration without other effects"],a:3,src:"CDC",exp:"Alcohol dilates blood vessels, which increases heat loss from the body's core and can worsen hypothermia despite the initial sensation of warmth."},
{id:36,cat:"first-aid",q:"What are the early warning signs of heat exhaustion?",o:["Heavy sweating, weakness, nausea, and cool moist skin","Dry hot skin, confusion, and sudden loss of consciousness","Absence of sweating, seizures, and dangerously high fever","Shivering, blue lips, and pale cold clammy extremities","Chest pain, shortness of breath, and tingling in arms"],a:0,src:"CDC",exp:"Heat exhaustion symptoms include heavy sweating, weakness, cold/pale/clammy skin, nausea or vomiting, dizziness, headache, and fainting."},
{id:37,cat:"first-aid",q:"How does heat stroke differ from heat exhaustion?",o:["Heat stroke always involves profuse heavy sweating","Heat stroke is generally a mild and minor condition","Heat stroke features temp above 103°F, hot red skin, possible unconsciousness","Heat exhaustion is considered far more dangerous overall","There is absolutely no difference between the two conditions"],a:2,src:"CDC",exp:"Heat stroke is a medical emergency with body temperature above 103°F, hot/red/dry or damp skin, rapid strong pulse, and possible unconsciousness. Call 911 immediately."},
{id:38,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the first thing you should do for a person with suspected heat stroke?",o:["Give them salt tablets to help restore electrolytes","Have them exercise to sweat out the excess heat","Wrap them in warm blankets to help induce sweating","Give them hot tea to help regulate their temperature","Call 911, move to cooler place, apply cool cloths"],a:4,src:"CDC",exp:"Heat stroke is a medical emergency. Call 911 immediately, move the person to a cooler environment, and try to reduce their body temperature with cool cloths or a cool bath."},
{id:39,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the first step if you suspect someone has been poisoned?",o:["Induce vomiting immediately using your fingers","Call Poison Control (1-800-222-1222) or 911","Give them several large glasses of milk to drink","Have them drink large amounts of water very quickly","Give them activated charcoal from the kitchen shelf"],a:1,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Call Poison Control at 1-800-222-1222 or 911 immediately. Do not induce vomiting unless specifically told to do so by a medical professional."},
{id:40,cat:"first-aid",q:"Why should you generally NOT induce vomiting after someone swallows a poison?",o:["Vomiting always works and is strongly recommended","Vomiting has absolutely no effect on ingested poisons","It is only considered dangerous for very young children","Some poisons cause more damage coming back up through esophagus","The poison is absorbed far too slowly to matter at all"],a:3,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Caustic or corrosive substances can cause additional burns and damage to the throat and esophagus if vomited. Always consult Poison Control first."},
{id:41,cat:"first-aid",q:"What information should you have ready when calling Poison Control?",o:["Victim's age, weight, substance, amount, and time ingested","Only your full name and your phone number on file","Just the specific name of the substance that was involved","Your health insurance information and current policy number","The name of the nearest hospital emergency room facility"],a:0,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Poison Control needs the victim's age, weight, the substance involved, the amount ingested, the time of ingestion, and any symptoms to provide proper guidance."},
{id:42,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the most common cause of severe allergic reactions (anaphylaxis)?",o:["Severe sunburn from extended ultraviolet exposure","Prolonged cold weather exposure leading to frostbite","Food allergens, insect stings, and certain medications","Chronic dehydration occurring over several days time","Excessive physical exercise and prolonged overexertion"],a:2,src:"CDC",exp:"The most common triggers for anaphylaxis are food allergens (such as peanuts and shellfish), insect stings (bees and wasps), and certain medications."},
{id:43,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the first-line treatment for anaphylaxis?",o:["Oral antihistamines like diphenhydramine or Benadryl","A strong dose of caffeine to stimulate circulation","Aspirin taken to reduce the inflammation and swelling","A cold compress applied firmly to the affected area","An epinephrine auto-injector such as an EpiPen"],a:4,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"Epinephrine administered via auto-injector (such as an EpiPen) is the first-line treatment for anaphylaxis. Antihistamines alone are not sufficient for severe reactions."},
{id:44,cat:"first-aid",q:"Where should an epinephrine auto-injector be administered?",o:["In the deltoid muscle of the upper arm area","In the outer middle portion of the thigh muscle","In the gluteal muscle of the buttock region","In the lower abdominal area near the hip bone","In the side of the neck near the shoulder area"],a:1,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"An epinephrine auto-injector should be injected into the outer middle thigh. It can be administered through clothing if necessary."},
{id:45,cat:"first-aid",q:"After administering epinephrine for anaphylaxis, what should you do next?",o:["The person is fully cured and needs no further care","Have them lie down and go to sleep right away","Give the person a full meal to restore their energy","Call 911 even if symptoms improve; a second reaction can occur","Apply ice to the injection site and do nothing more"],a:3,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"Always call 911 after administering epinephrine. Anaphylaxis can recur (biphasic reaction), and the person needs medical monitoring even if symptoms improve."},
{id:46,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the proper way to clean a minor wound?",o:["Rinse with clean running water, wash around with soap","Use hydrogen peroxide generously to kill all the germs","Apply rubbing alcohol directly into the open wound area","Use very hot water to thoroughly sterilize the wound","Leave it uncleaned to avoid disturbing healing tissue"],a:0,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Rinse the wound under clean running water and gently wash the area around the wound with soap. Avoid using hydrogen peroxide or alcohol directly in the wound as they can damage tissue."},
{id:47,cat:"first-aid",q:"When should you seek medical attention for a wound?",o:["Only if it becomes visibly infected several days later","Only for wounds that are located on the face or head","For deep wounds, uncontrolled bleeding, bites, or debris","Never because all wounds will heal fully on their own","Only if the wound was caused by a rusty metal object"],a:2,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Seek medical attention for deep or gaping wounds, wounds that won't stop bleeding, puncture wounds, animal bites, wounds with debris or embedded objects, or signs of infection."},
{id:48,cat:"first-aid",q:"How often should a tetanus booster be given for adults?",o:["Every single year without any exception at all","Every 5 years as recommended by the CDC guidelines","Every 20 years for most otherwise healthy adults","Only once in an entire lifetime is fully sufficient","Every 10 years as recommended by CDC guidelines"],a:4,src:"CDC",exp:"The CDC recommends a tetanus booster (Td or Tdap) every 10 years for adults. A booster may be given sooner for certain dirty or deep wounds."},
{id:49,cat:"first-aid",q:"What are the signs of a wound infection?",o:["The wound is healing normally and scabbing over well","Increasing redness, swelling, warmth, pain, and pus","The wound appears dry, closed, and completely painless","Steadily decreased redness and swelling over the days","Only mild itching felt around the wound edge area"],a:1,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Signs of wound infection include increasing pain, redness, swelling, warmth around the wound, pus or cloudy drainage, red streaks, fever, and swollen lymph nodes."},
{id:50,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is a concussion?",o:["A minor headache that always resolves quickly on its own","A bruise that forms on the outer surface of the brain","A fracture of the skull without any brain involvement","A traumatic brain injury from a bump, blow, or jolt","A specific type of migraine triggered by physical activity"],a:3,src:"CDC",exp:"A concussion is a type of traumatic brain injury (TBI) caused by a bump, blow, or jolt to the head or a hit to the body that causes the brain to move rapidly inside the skull."},
{id:51,cat:"first-aid",q:"What are the danger signs of a concussion that require immediate emergency care?",o:["One pupil larger than the other, worsening headache, slurred speech, repeated vomiting, or seizures","A mild headache that comes and goes without any other accompanying neurological symptoms","Feeling slightly tired or fatigued after bumping your head but otherwise functioning normally","A small visible bump on the head with minor tenderness at the site of impact","Brief dizziness that resolves within a few seconds and does not return afterward"],a:0,src:"CDC",exp:"Danger signs include unequal pupils, worsening headache, slurred speech, repeated vomiting, seizures, loss of consciousness, and increasing confusion. Call 911 immediately."},
{id:52,cat:"first-aid",q:"Should you move a person with a suspected spinal injury?",o:["Yes, always reposition them into a more comfortable and supportive posture","Yes, carefully roll them over to visually inspect the back for potential injuries","Only if there is immediate life-threatening danger such as fire","Gently move them to a seated position so they can breathe more easily","Roll them onto their side immediately to prevent any potential choking hazards"],a:2,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Do not move a person with a suspected spinal injury unless there is immediate danger (fire, flood, etc.). Moving them can worsen a spinal cord injury. Wait for EMS."},
{id:53,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the recovery position used for?",o:["Treating cardiac arrest by restoring blood circulation to the heart","Applying direct pressure to stop severe bleeding from traumatic wounds","Performing hands-only CPR on an unresponsive adult victim","Immobilizing and stabilizing a broken leg to prevent further bone damage","Keeping an unconscious breathing person's airway open"],a:4,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"The recovery position (on their side) helps keep the airway open and allows fluids to drain from the mouth, preventing choking in an unconscious person who is breathing."},
{id:54,cat:"first-aid",q:"When performing CPR on a child (ages 1-puberty), what is the compression depth?",o:["At least 2.4 inches, which equals roughly half the anterior-posterior chest diameter","About 2 inches (one-third the depth of the chest)","About 1 inch, using only two fingertips placed on the lower sternum","About 3 inches deep to ensure adequate blood circulation throughout the body","About 0.5 inches, applying very gentle pressure with the heel of one hand"],a:1,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"For children ages 1 to puberty, compress the chest about 2 inches, or approximately one-third the anterior-posterior diameter of the chest."},
{id:55,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the proper first aid for a knocked-out permanent tooth?",o:["Scrub the tooth thoroughly with a brush and antibacterial soap, then firmly push it back into the socket","Discard the tooth since adult teeth cannot be successfully reimplanted once fully dislodged","Wrap it carefully in a dry tissue, place it in a sealed container, and wait several days before seeing a dentist","Handle by the crown, rinse gently, try to reinsert or store in milk, and see a dentist immediately","Soak it in rubbing alcohol or hydrogen peroxide solution to sterilize it before handling"],a:3,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Handle the tooth by the crown (not the root), rinse gently without scrubbing, attempt to reinsert it, or store it in milk or saliva, and see a dentist within 30 minutes if possible."},
{id:56,cat:"first-aid",q:"What does the mnemonic FAST stand for in stroke recognition?",o:["Face drooping, Arm weakness, Speech difficulty, Time to call 911","First Aid Stroke Treatment — a comprehensive emergency medical response protocol","Feel the patient's pulse, Assess their neurological status, Stabilize the cervical spine, Transport immediately","Fast Action Saves Time — a general principle applied across all acute emergency situations","Find the nearest hospital, Alert the emergency department, Support vital functions, Treat underlying cause"],a:0,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"FAST stands for Face drooping, Arm weakness, Speech difficulty, and Time to call 911. Quick recognition and treatment of stroke can save lives and reduce disability."},
{id:57,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the critical time window for stroke treatment with clot-busting medication?",o:["Within 24 hours of the very first onset of any neurological symptoms","Within 1 week, as long as symptoms are still actively present and progressing","Within 3 to 4.5 hours of symptom onset","Within 12 hours, provided a CT scan confirms the type of stroke beforehand","There is no established time limit for administering clot-busting medication effectively"],a:2,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"Clot-busting medication (tPA) is most effective when given within 3 to 4.5 hours of stroke symptom onset. Every minute counts."},
{id:58,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the proper response to a seizure?",o:["Restrain the person firmly to prevent any involuntary movements that could cause self-injury","Put a wallet, spoon, or similar object in their mouth to prevent them from biting their tongue","Perform full CPR with chest compressions and rescue breaths throughout the entire seizure","Pour cold water on their face and shake them vigorously to bring them back to consciousness","Protect them from injury, cushion their head, and time the seizure"],a:4,src:"CDC",exp:"During a seizure, protect the person from injury, cushion their head, turn them on their side after the seizure, and time it. Never restrain or put objects in their mouth."},
{id:59,cat:"first-aid",q:"When should you call 911 for a seizure?",o:["Only if the person has absolutely never experienced a seizure before in their entire life","If it lasts more than 5 minutes, they don't regain consciousness, or another follows quickly","Only if the person has completely and permanently stopped breathing with no signs of recovery","Never — seizures are a normal neurological event that always resolve on their own without intervention","Only if the person experiencing the seizure is a young child under the age of twelve"],a:1,src:"CDC",exp:"Call 911 if a seizure lasts more than 5 minutes, the person does not regain consciousness, another seizure occurs soon after, or the person is injured, pregnant, or diabetic."},
{id:60,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the first step in treating a snakebite?",o:["Cut the wound open with a knife and attempt to suck the venom out before it spreads","Apply a tight tourniquet several inches above the bite to completely restrict blood flow","Apply ice or a frozen compress directly to the bite wound to slow venom absorption","Keep the person calm and still, remove jewelry near the bite, and call 911","Give the person alcohol or a strong painkiller to help reduce the immediate pain"],a:3,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Keep the person calm and immobile, remove rings or jewelry near the bite before swelling starts, keep the bite below heart level if possible, and seek immediate medical help."},
{id:61,cat:"first-aid",q:"Which of these should you NOT do for a snakebite?",o:["Try to suck out the venom or cut the wound","Keep the person as calm and still as possible while waiting for help","Call 911 or emergency medical services right away","Note the snake's appearance, color, and markings for identification at the hospital","Remove constrictive clothing, jewelry, and accessories near the bite site"],a:0,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Never cut the wound, try to suck out venom, apply ice, use a tourniquet, or apply electric shock. These outdated methods can cause additional harm."},
{id:62,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the first aid for a bee sting in a person without allergies?",o:["Squeeze the stinger firmly between your fingers and pull it straight out from the skin","Ignore it completely since bee stings in non-allergic individuals require no treatment whatsoever","Scrape the stinger away with a flat edge, wash the area, and apply a cold pack","Apply a heated compress or warm cloth directly to the sting site to neutralize the venom","Cover the sting area with a thick layer of mud or clay to draw out the venom naturally"],a:2,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Scrape the stinger off with a flat-edged object (like a credit card) rather than squeezing it, which can release more venom. Wash the area and apply a cold pack."},
{id:63,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the primary first aid concern for a person who has been struck by lightning?",o:["They are still electrically charged and extremely dangerous for anyone to touch directly","Look carefully for exit wounds only, as entry wounds from lightning strikes are rarely significant","Treat only the visible surface burns, since lightning injuries are limited to external skin damage","Wait for the storm to pass completely before approaching or attempting to help the victim","Check for cardiac arrest and begin CPR if needed; they are safe to touch"],a:4,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Lightning victims do not carry an electrical charge and are safe to touch. The primary concern is cardiac arrest; check for breathing and pulse and begin CPR if needed."},
{id:64,cat:"first-aid",q:"How should you treat a blister from friction (such as from hiking)?",o:["Pop it immediately with a sterilized needle and drain all the fluid out completely","Leave it intact, clean the area, and protect it with a bandage","Peel off the entire layer of blistered skin to allow the area underneath to dry and heal faster","Apply a thin layer of super glue or liquid adhesive over the blister to create a protective seal","Ignore it entirely, as friction blisters always heal quickly without any intervention needed"],a:1,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Do not pop blisters. The skin acts as a natural barrier against infection. Clean the area, apply a protective bandage or moleskin, and let it heal."},
{id:65,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the best way to remove a tick?",o:["Burn it off by holding a lit match or heated needle close to the tick's body","Apply a thick layer of petroleum jelly over the tick to suffocate it and make it release","Twist it firmly in a counterclockwise direction while simultaneously pulling upward","Grasp it close to the skin with fine-tipped tweezers and pull straight up with steady pressure","Squeeze the tick's engorged body firmly between your fingers and yank it out quickly"],a:3,src:"CDC",exp:"Use fine-tipped tweezers to grasp the tick as close to the skin surface as possible. Pull upward with steady, even pressure. Clean the bite area and your hands after removal."},
{id:66,cat:"first-aid",q:"After removing a tick, why is it important to monitor the bite area?",o:["To watch for a bull's-eye rash or other signs of tick-borne illness such as Lyme disease","All tick bites inevitably lead to serious infection regardless of species or duration of attachment","The tick's head might regenerate and grow back into a new tick at the original bite location","There is actually no medical reason to monitor the area after a tick has been properly removed","To determine whether the tick that bit you was male or female, which affects treatment options"],a:0,src:"CDC",exp:"Monitor for 30 days for signs of tick-borne illness, especially a bull's-eye rash (erythema migrans), fever, fatigue, or joint pain, which may indicate Lyme disease."},
{id:67,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the proper way to treat a nosebleed?",o:["Tilt the head back as far as possible and swallow any blood that drains into the throat","Lie completely flat on your back with your legs elevated above the level of your heart","Lean slightly forward, pinch the soft part of the nose, and hold for 10 to 15 minutes","Stuff tissue or cotton gauze as deep into the nostril as possible to absorb the blood","Blow your nose as hard as you can repeatedly to forcefully clear out all the blood"],a:2,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Lean slightly forward to prevent swallowing blood, pinch the soft part of the nose shut, and hold for 10 to 15 minutes. Do not tilt the head back."},
{id:68,cat:"first-aid",q:"What does it mean when a person's skin turns blue or gray (cyanosis)?",o:["They are significantly overheated and experiencing dangerous levels of heat exhaustion","They have developed a moderate to severe sunburn from prolonged ultraviolet radiation exposure","They are experiencing an acute episode of dangerously elevated high blood pressure","They are well-hydrated, which sometimes causes temporary discoloration in the extremities","They may not be getting enough oxygen"],a:4,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Cyanosis (bluish or grayish discoloration of the skin, lips, or nail beds) indicates inadequate oxygenation and is a sign of a serious medical emergency."},
{id:69,cat:"first-aid",q:"For a diabetic emergency, if the person is conscious and able to swallow, what should you give them?",o:["Administer their insulin immediately, regardless of whether their blood sugar is high or low","A sugar-containing food or drink such as fruit juice","A diet soda or other sugar-free artificially sweetened beverage to help stabilize them","Salty snacks like pretzels or chips to help restore their electrolyte balance quickly","Nothing at all — do not give them any food or drink and simply wait for EMS to arrive"],a:1,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"If a diabetic person is conscious and you are unsure whether their blood sugar is high or low, giving sugar is generally safer. Give fruit juice, regular soda, or glucose tablets."},
{id:70,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the correct first aid for an embedded (impaled) object in a wound?",o:["Pull the object out immediately so that you can apply direct pressure to control bleeding","Carefully cut the object flush with the skin surface using a sharp knife or trauma shears","Push the object in deeper to apply internal pressure and thereby reduce the external bleeding","Leave the object in place, stabilize it with bulky dressings, and call 911","Twist the object gently back and forth in a rotating motion to loosen it before careful removal"],a:3,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Never remove an impaled object as it may be controlling bleeding. Stabilize it in place with bulky dressings and seek immediate emergency medical care."},
{id:71,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the recommended first aid for a suspected heart attack?",o:["Have them chew an aspirin (if not allergic), call 911, and be ready to perform CPR","Have the person lie completely flat on their back and elevate their legs above heart level","Give them a strong cup of coffee or caffeinated energy drink to stimulate the heart muscle","Apply a cold compress wrapped in cloth to the center of the chest to reduce cardiac inflammation","Have them take a hot shower immediately to improve blood circulation throughout the body"],a:0,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"Call 911, have the person chew one adult aspirin (325 mg) or four baby aspirin if they are not allergic, keep them calm, and be prepared to perform CPR if they become unresponsive."},
{id:72,cat:"first-aid",q:"What are common warning signs of a heart attack?",o:["Pain exclusively isolated to the left arm with no other symptoms present whatsoever","Severe headache accompanied by blurred vision only, without any chest discomfort involved","Chest discomfort, shortness of breath, pain radiating to arms/jaw/back, nausea, and cold sweat","Bilateral leg cramps and foot pain that worsens with walking or physical activity","Persistent ringing in the ears accompanied by mild dizziness and temporary hearing loss"],a:2,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"Heart attack symptoms include uncomfortable pressure or pain in the chest, shortness of breath, discomfort in the arms, back, neck, jaw, or stomach, cold sweat, nausea, and lightheadedness."},
{id:73,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the primary danger of drowning that occurs even after rescue?",o:["Severe sunburn from prolonged exposure to direct sunlight while in the water","Painful muscle cramps throughout the body that persist for several days after the incident","Progressive dehydration caused by ingesting large amounts of chlorinated or salt water","Hypothermia only, which can develop within minutes of being removed from the water","Secondary drowning, where fluid in the lungs causes breathing problems hours later"],a:4,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"After a drowning incident, water in the lungs can cause inflammation and fluid buildup hours later (secondary or delayed drowning), making medical evaluation essential even if the person seems fine."},
{id:74,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the reach-throw-row-go order in water rescue?",o:["A competitive swimming technique used in lifeguard training and certification courses","A prioritized approach: safest to most dangerous method","A standardized sequence of CPR steps specifically designed for drowning victims","A specialized method for treating hypothermia in victims rescued from cold water","A series of internationally recognized hand signals used to communicate a call for help"],a:1,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Reach-throw-row-go prioritizes rescue methods from safest to riskiest: reach with an object, throw a flotation device, row a boat to them, and only go in the water as a last resort."},
{id:75,cat:"first-aid",q:"How should you perform rescue breathing for a drowning victim who has a pulse but is not breathing?",o:["Deliver 5 quick breaths in rapid succession and then wait several minutes before reassessing","10 breaths per minute for children, counting carefully between each individual rescue breath delivered","Continuous chest compressions only, at a rate of 100 to 120 compressions per minute without pause","Give 1 rescue breath every 5 to 6 seconds for an adult","Blow as hard and forcefully as possible into their mouth to overcome any water in the airways"],a:3,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"For an adult with a pulse but not breathing, give 1 rescue breath every 5 to 6 seconds (10 to 12 breaths per minute), checking for a pulse every 2 minutes."},
{id:76,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the purpose of a pressure bandage?",o:["To apply continuous direct pressure to a wound to help control bleeding","To keep a wound warm and maintain consistent temperature around the injured tissue","To serve exclusively as a holder for keeping an ice pack securely positioned on an injury","To act as a tourniquet by completely restricting all arterial blood flow to the entire limb","To absorb environmental moisture from the surrounding air and keep the wound area dry"],a:0,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"A pressure bandage applies firm, continuous direct pressure to a wound to help control bleeding while keeping the wound covered and protected."},
{id:77,cat:"first-aid",q:"What type of injury can result from rapid changes in air pressure, such as during an explosion?",o:["A mild sprain affecting the ligaments and surrounding soft tissue of the ankle joint","A superficial paper cut on the hands or exposed areas of skin from flying debris","Blast injury affecting the lungs, ears, and hollow organs","A minor bruise or contusion limited to the surface layers of the skin","A standard sunburn caused by ultraviolet radiation released during the blast event"],a:2,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Blast injuries from rapid pressure changes can damage the lungs, rupture eardrums, and injure hollow organs like the intestines, even without external wounds."},
{id:78,cat:"first-aid",q:"What should you do if a person has frostbite on their fingers?",o:["Rub the fingers vigorously back and forth with your hands to generate friction and warm them quickly","Place the fingers directly in hot water above 104°F to rewarm the tissue as rapidly as possible","Apply handfuls of snow to the frostbitten area, as the cold will stimulate increased blood circulation","Pop any blisters that form on the fingers so the fluid inside does not cause further tissue damage","Warm gradually in lukewarm water (98-102°F) and seek medical attention"],a:4,src:"CDC",exp:"Warm frostbitten areas gradually in lukewarm water (98-102°F). Do not rub, use hot water, or apply direct heat. Seek medical attention. Do not re-warm if refreezing is possible."},
{id:79,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the difference between frostbite and frostnip?",o:["There is no meaningful medical difference between frostbite and frostnip; they are interchangeable terms","Frostnip is mild and reversible with warming, while frostbite involves tissue freezing and potential permanent damage","Frostnip is considerably more severe and dangerous than frostbite and requires immediate surgical intervention","Frostbite only affects exposed skin on the face, while frostnip can occur anywhere on the body","Frostnip almost always requires partial or full amputation of the affected digits or extremities"],a:1,src:"CDC",exp:"Frostnip is a mild, reversible cold injury causing numbness and color changes. Frostbite is more severe, involving actual tissue freezing that can cause permanent damage."},
{id:80,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the correct way to use a sling for an arm injury?",o:["Tie it as tightly as possible in a knot directly against the back of the neck over the cervical spine","Wrap the sling material firmly around the waist and secure the injured arm against the abdomen","Let the arm hang freely and naturally at the side without any form of support or immobilization","Support the forearm across the chest with the hand slightly elevated, secured with a triangular bandage","Position the injured arm behind the back and secure it there with the sling tied across the chest"],a:3,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"A sling should support the injured forearm across the chest with the hand slightly higher than the elbow. Use a triangular bandage tied at the side of the neck, not the back."},
{id:81,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the most effective way to prevent infection when treating a wound in a wilderness setting?",o:["Irrigate the wound thoroughly with clean water","Apply a layer of dirt or soil directly to the wound, as the natural minerals help stop bleeding","Cauterize the wound immediately using a heated knife blade or a burning stick from the campfire","Leave the wound completely open and uncovered so that fresh air can dry it out naturally","Apply a thick coat of tree sap or pine resin to seal the wound and create a waterproof barrier"],a:0,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Thorough wound irrigation with clean water removes debris and bacteria, significantly reducing infection risk. Use at least half a liter of clean water with pressure irrigation if possible."},
{id:82,cat:"first-aid",q:"What condition causes rapid breathing, tingling in hands and feet, and lightheadedness due to excessive breathing?",o:["Heart attack with atypical presentation","Acute asthma attack","Hyperventilation","Hypothermia","Ischemic stroke"],a:2,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Hyperventilation is rapid or deep breathing that causes carbon dioxide levels to drop, leading to tingling, lightheadedness, and muscle spasms. Have the person slow their breathing."},
{id:83,cat:"first-aid",q:"Which vital sign is most important to monitor in an unconscious person?",o:["Blood pressure readings taken at regular intervals","Pupil size and reactivity to light","Core body temperature","Skin color and capillary refill time","Breathing and airway"],a:4,src:"AHA Guidelines",exp:"Breathing and airway maintenance is the most critical vital sign to monitor in an unconscious person, as airway obstruction is the most immediate life threat."},
{id:84,cat:"first-aid",q:"What is the purpose of nitrile or latex gloves in a first aid kit?",o:["To keep your hands warm and maintain dexterity in cold weather emergency situations","To protect both rescuer and victim from bloodborne pathogens","To significantly improve grip strength when handling wet or slippery medical equipment","To present a clean and professional appearance when providing care to injured persons","To prevent the victim from developing allergic reactions to adhesive bandages and medical tape"],a:1,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Disposable gloves provide a barrier against bloodborne pathogens, protecting both the rescuer from the victim's blood and the victim from contamination."},
{id:85,cat:"first-aid",q:"In a mass casualty event, what triage color tag indicates a victim who needs immediate life-saving treatment?",o:["Green, which designates minor injuries and walking wounded who can wait for treatment","Yellow, indicating delayed-priority patients who have serious but non-life-threatening injuries","Black, meaning the victim is deceased or has injuries incompatible with survival given available resources","Red (immediate)","White, meaning the patient has been assessed, treated, and formally dismissed from the scene"],a:3,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"In the START triage system, red tags indicate victims who need immediate life-saving intervention. Green is minor/walking wounded, yellow is delayed, and black is deceased or expectant."},
{id:86,cat:"shelter",q:"What is the most important factor when choosing a location for an emergency shelter?",o:["Protection from wind, rain, and flooding while being near water and resources","Proximity to an elevated area with a scenic panoramic view of the surrounding landscape","Choosing the highest possible elevation point regardless of wind exposure or available materials","Building directly on a dry riverbed for convenient and immediate access to a water source","Selecting an area that receives the maximum amount of direct sunlight throughout the entire day"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Choose a location protected from wind, precipitation, and potential flooding. Being near a water source and building materials is important, but avoid dry riverbeds and valley floors."},
{id:87,cat:"shelter",q:"What is a lean-to shelter?",o:["A permanent concrete structure with reinforced walls and a solid foundation","A fully underground bunker designed to withstand extreme weather and provide long-term protection","A single-sloped shelter built by leaning materials against a ridgepole","A poorly constructed shelter that leans to one side because of imbalanced weight distribution","A commercially manufactured lightweight tent designed for recreational camping and backpacking trips"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"A lean-to is one of the simplest emergency shelters, made by leaning branches, logs, or other materials against a horizontal ridgepole supported between two trees or posts."},
{id:88,cat:"shelter",q:"Why is insulation important in an emergency shelter?",o:["It makes the shelter more visually appealing and organized, improving morale during a survival scenario","It has no practical benefit and is generally considered an unnecessary use of time and energy","It serves primarily as a barrier to keep insects, spiders, and other small creatures out of the shelter","It only matters in hot weather environments where you need to block radiant heat from the sun","It prevents heat loss to the ground and air, which can prevent hypothermia"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Insulation prevents body heat from being conducted to the cold ground (the biggest source of heat loss) and helps maintain a survivable temperature inside the shelter."},
{id:89,cat:"shelter",q:"What is the best natural insulation material for a ground bed in an emergency shelter?",o:["Rocks and flat stones arranged in a single layer across the floor of the shelter","Dry leaves, pine needles, dry grass, or evergreen boughs","Wet leaves packed tightly together to form a moisture-resistant compressed layer","Mud applied in a thick even coating across the entire shelter floor surface","Sand spread evenly to create a smooth and level sleeping surface inside the shelter"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Dry natural materials like leaves, pine needles, dry grass, or evergreen boughs create air pockets that trap body heat and insulate from the cold ground. Use at least 6 inches."},
{id:90,cat:"shelter",q:"In a cold weather survival situation, how thick should your ground insulation layer ideally be?",o:["Approximately 1 inch of loosely gathered material placed between you and the bare ground","No ground insulation is needed because body heat alone is sufficient to stay warm on cold ground","Less than half an inch, just enough to provide a thin protective barrier against the surface","At least 4 to 6 inches","A minimum of 12 inches to ensure maximum thermal protection from the frozen ground beneath"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"A minimum of 4 to 6 inches of compressed insulation material between you and the ground helps prevent conductive heat loss, which is a primary cause of hypothermia."},
{id:91,cat:"shelter",q:"What is a debris hut?",o:["A small, enclosed shelter made from sticks covered in leaves and debris","A house constructed entirely from salvaged construction debris, scrap wood, and reclaimed materials","A loosely assembled pile of trash and discarded materials arranged as a basic windbreak","A commercially manufactured camping product sold at outdoor recreation and sporting goods retailers","A semi-permanent shelter assembled from scavenged corrugated sheet metal and industrial materials"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"A debris hut is a small emergency shelter with a ridgepole frame covered in layers of leaves, pine needles, and other forest debris for insulation and waterproofing."},
{id:92,cat:"shelter",q:"Why should an emergency shelter be built small rather than large?",o:["Large shelters tend to attract predatory animals and other dangerous wildlife to the campsite area","Local building codes and ordinances typically require permits for any structure over a certain size","A smaller shelter retains body heat more effectively","Small shelters are considered more visually appealing and blend in better with natural surroundings","There is no practical advantage whatsoever to building a small shelter over a larger one"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"A smaller shelter is easier to heat with body warmth alone, requires less building material and energy to construct, and provides better protection from wind and cold."},
{id:93,cat:"shelter",q:"What is the primary purpose of a space blanket (emergency Mylar blanket)?",o:["To use as a heat-resistant cooking surface for preparing food directly over hot coals and embers","To provide a reliable protective barrier against mosquitoes, ticks, and other biting insects","To signal rescue aircraft during daylight hours only, using the reflective surface as a mirror","To serve exclusively as a rainwater collection device for gathering and storing drinking water","To reflect up to 90% of body heat back to the person"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Emergency space blankets are made of Mylar that reflects up to 90% of radiated body heat back to the user, helping prevent hypothermia in emergency situations."},
{id:94,cat:"shelter",q:"When sheltering in a vehicle during a winter storm, what should you do?",o:["Run the engine continuously at idle with all windows completely sealed shut to maximize interior warmth","Run the engine and heater about 10 minutes each hour, cracking a downwind window slightly","Abandon the vehicle immediately and walk in the direction of the nearest town to find help","Turn off the engine entirely and seal every opening completely to conserve all remaining body heat","Remove all heavy clothing to prevent excessive sweating, which accelerates dangerous heat loss"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Run the engine about 10 minutes per hour for heat, crack a downwind window slightly to prevent carbon monoxide poisoning, and make sure the exhaust pipe is clear of snow."},
{id:95,cat:"shelter",q:"What is the biggest danger of using fuel-burning heaters or stoves inside an enclosed shelter?",o:["They attract bears, wolves, and other predatory wildlife to the shelter due to the smell of fuel","They are prohibitively expensive and consume fuel at an unsustainably high rate in cold conditions","They produce excessive amounts of bright light that can compromise your position and attract attention","Carbon monoxide poisoning from inadequate ventilation","They generate too much noise, making it impossible to hear approaching danger or rescue signals"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Fuel-burning heaters and stoves produce carbon monoxide, an odorless, colorless gas that can be fatal in enclosed spaces. Always ensure adequate ventilation."},
{id:96,cat:"shelter",q:"During a tornado warning, what is the safest location in a house without a basement?",o:["An interior room on the lowest floor, away from windows","Near the largest windows so you can visually monitor the tornado's path and direction of movement","The attic, where you are above the most dangerous ground-level wind forces and flying debris","The garage, which typically has the strongest structural reinforcement in a residential building","An upper-floor bedroom located on the side of the house facing away from the approaching storm"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"An interior room on the lowest floor (such as a bathroom, closet, or hallway) away from windows offers the most protection from tornado winds and flying debris."},
{id:97,cat:"shelter",q:"What does 'shelter-in-place' mean during a chemical or radiological emergency?",o:["Evacuate immediately to the nearest designated public emergency shelter or community center","Stand outside in an open area and wait for official instructions from emergency management authorities","Go to a sealed interior room, close all openings, and turn off ventilation","Drive directly to the closest hospital emergency department for decontamination and medical screening","Go to the roof of the building where contaminated air is less likely to accumulate at ground level"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Shelter-in-place means going indoors immediately, sealing doors, windows, and vents with plastic sheeting and tape, and turning off HVAC systems to prevent contaminated air from entering."},
{id:98,cat:"shelter",q:"What material is recommended for sealing windows and doors during a shelter-in-place chemical emergency?",o:["Multiple layers of newspaper soaked in water and pressed firmly against all openings and gaps","Heavy cardboard sheets attached with wood glue or a strong adhesive compound around all window frames","Several sheets of aluminum foil layered over each window opening and crimped tightly around the edges","Wet towels only, rolled and placed along the base of doors and draped over window sills","Pre-cut plastic sheeting and duct tape"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"FEMA recommends pre-cut plastic sheeting (6 mil thick) and duct tape to seal windows, doors, and vents during a chemical or radiological shelter-in-place event."},
{id:99,cat:"shelter",q:"How much plastic sheeting should you have pre-cut for shelter-in-place preparedness?",o:["One small roll for the entire house, cutting pieces as needed during the actual emergency event","Enough to cover all windows, doors, and vents in one designated room, cut several inches wider than each opening","Only enough for one window, since partial sealing is sufficient to reduce airborne contaminant levels","No plastic sheeting is needed if you have a modern home with energy-efficient windows and good insulation","Exactly the size of each opening with no overlap, trimmed precisely to fit flush against the frame"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Pre-measure and cut plastic sheeting several inches wider than each window, door, and vent in your designated shelter-in-place room so you can seal quickly during an emergency."},
{id:100,cat:"shelter",q:"In a hot climate survival situation, what type of shelter is most appropriate?",o:["A fully enclosed dark shelter with thick walls and a sealed entrance to block all outside light","A shelter with its primary opening facing directly into the sun for maximum interior illumination","An underground bunker that is completely sealed from outside air circulation and ventilation","A shade shelter with good airflow, elevated off the ground if possible","A heavily insulated debris hut packed with dense layers of leaves, moss, and other organic material"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"In hot climates, shade is the priority. An open-sided shelter with good ventilation prevents heat buildup. Elevating it off the ground allows air to circulate underneath."},
{id:101,cat:"shelter",q:"What is the purpose of a reflector wall near a lean-to shelter?",o:["To reflect heat from a fire back toward the shelter","To block the view from outside and provide concealment from wildlife or other people","To serve as a structural support that holds up the lean-to frame","To act as an additional rain barrier for the shelter entrance","To attract rescue teams by creating a visible landmark"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"A reflector wall made of logs or rocks positioned behind a fire and opposite the lean-to opening reflects heat back into the shelter, significantly increasing warmth."},
{id:102,cat:"shelter",q:"When building a snow shelter (quinzee), why should you let the snow pile set for at least an hour before hollowing?",o:["To let the snow gradually melt and refreeze into a solid ice block","To give any burrowing animals time to vacate the disturbed snow pile area","To allow the snow crystals to bond and sinter","It looks better after setting and compacts into a more aesthetically pleasing form","There is no practical reason to wait before you begin hollowing"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"After piling snow, the crystals undergo sintering (bonding together) which strengthens the structure. Waiting at least 1-2 hours before hollowing prevents collapse."},
{id:103,cat:"shelter",q:"What is the ideal thickness for the walls of a snow shelter?",o:["1 to 2 inches at most to allow light to pass through for visibility","It does not matter as long as the walls are structurally sound and uniform","About 3 feet to maximize thermal mass and wind resistance","As thin as possible to conserve the amount of effort required during construction","8 to 12 inches"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Snow shelter walls should be about 8 to 12 inches thick to provide adequate insulation while maintaining structural integrity. Insert sticks as guides while hollowing to gauge thickness."},
{id:104,cat:"shelter",q:"Why is ventilation critical in a snow shelter?",o:["To let in natural light so occupants can see and maintain a normal circadian rhythm","To prevent carbon dioxide buildup and suffocation","To allow smoke from a campfire built inside to properly exhaust out of the shelter","Snow shelters do not need ventilation because snow is naturally porous and breathable","To keep the interior temperature consistently below freezing to prevent structural melting"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Snow shelters can become airtight, and body heat along with breathing can cause dangerous CO2 buildup. Always maintain at least one ventilation hole in the roof or wall."},
{id:105,cat:"shelter",q:"What household room is typically designated as the best shelter-in-place room?",o:["The kitchen because it has running water and stored food supplies readily available","The garage since it provides easy vehicle access for a quick evacuation if needed","The living room with large windows for monitoring outside conditions visually","An interior room above ground level with few or no windows","The attic because it is the highest point in the structure away from ground-level threats"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Choose an interior room above ground level (chemicals can settle to low areas) with few or no windows, the fewest doors, and access to water if possible, like a bathroom."},
{id:106,cat:"shelter",q:"What is a tarp shelter's main advantage over a natural debris shelter?",o:["It can be set up faster with less energy","It is always warmer because the synthetic material traps heat more effectively than organic debris","It blends into the natural environment better due to its low visual profile","It provides significantly better insulation against cold temperatures and wind","It does not need any cordage, stakes, or additional rigging materials to set up"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"A tarp shelter can be erected in minutes with minimal energy, while a debris shelter may take hours to build. In survival situations, conserving energy is critical."},
{id:107,cat:"shelter",q:"What knot is commonly recommended for securing a ridgeline for a tarp shelter?",o:["A square knot, which is the standard all-purpose binding knot used in most applications","A granny knot tied with multiple overhand loops for additional security","A bowline or taut-line hitch","A basic slip knot, which allows for fast release when breaking camp","No knot is needed since wrapping the line around the tree several times provides enough friction"],a:2,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"A taut-line hitch is adjustable and maintains tension on a ridgeline, while a bowline creates a secure, non-slipping loop. Both are excellent for shelter construction."},
{id:108,cat:"shelter",q:"In an earthquake, what is the recommended protective action if you are indoors?",o:["Run outside immediately to get away from the building structure as fast as possible","Lie flat in the middle of the room and cover your head with your arms","Stand in a doorway since older construction guidelines considered them reinforced","Get near windows to escape the building quickly if it starts to collapse","Drop, Cover, and Hold On under sturdy furniture"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Drop to your hands and knees, take Cover under a sturdy desk or table, and Hold On until the shaking stops. Do not run outside during shaking as falling debris is a major hazard."},
{id:109,cat:"shelter",q:"After an earthquake, what should you check before re-entering your home?",o:["Whether the TV and other electronics still work properly after the shaking","For structural damage, gas leaks, and downed power lines","If the mail has been delivered since postal services may still be operating normally","Whether the lawn and landscaping needs attention from any debris that may have fallen","Nothing; it is always safe to re-enter your home after the shaking has fully stopped"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Check for structural damage, smell for gas leaks, look for downed power lines, and check for fire hazards before re-entering. If you smell gas, leave immediately and call authorities."},
{id:110,cat:"shelter",q:"What is the main hazard of seeking shelter under a highway overpass during a tornado?",o:["There is no hazard; it is widely considered a safe and recommended location for tornado shelter","It is too dark to see approaching debris or other vehicles seeking the same shelter","The overpass may collapse from the combined weight of multiple cars parked underneath it","Wind speeds increase under the overpass, and there is no debris protection","Traffic congestion is the only real concern since many people have the same idea simultaneously"],a:3,src:"NOAA",exp:"Highway overpasses create a wind tunnel effect that actually increases wind speed. They offer no protection from flying debris, which is the primary cause of tornado injuries and deaths."},
{id:111,cat:"shelter",q:"What natural feature can serve as an emergency wind shelter?",o:["A depression, thick grove of trees, or leeward side of a rock formation","The windward side of a mountain where you can monitor approaching weather systems","A hilltop that provides good visibility and access to rescue aircraft","A flat open field where wind passes evenly without creating dangerous turbulence","A dry riverbed that offers natural walls on both sides for wind deflection"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Natural depressions, dense tree groves, and the leeward (downwind) side of large rock formations or hills provide natural wind protection for emergency shelters."},
{id:112,cat:"shelter",q:"Why should you avoid building a shelter at the bottom of a valley or canyon?",o:["There is too much direct sunlight reflecting off the valley walls during daytime hours","The ground is always rocky and difficult to excavate for stakes or ground anchors","Cold air pools in low areas, and valleys are prone to flash flooding","There are typically too many trees, making it difficult to find a clear spot for construction","Animals never inhabit valleys, so there would be no food sources available nearby"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Cold air sinks to the lowest points (cold air pooling), making valley floors significantly colder at night. Valleys and canyons are also highly susceptible to flash flooding."},
{id:113,cat:"shelter",q:"What is the safest place to shelter during a hurricane if you cannot evacuate?",o:["In a mobile home that has been properly anchored and tied down to its foundation","In a car parked in a garage or other enclosed structure away from the main wind path","On the top floor for the best vantage point to monitor the storm's progression","In the garage because the large door can be reinforced with bracing materials","A small interior room on the lowest floor of a sturdy building"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"If you cannot evacuate, shelter in a small interior room on the lowest floor of a well-built permanent structure, away from windows, skylights, and glass doors."},
{id:114,cat:"shelter",q:"What is the 'dead air space' principle in shelter building?",o:["Air that has no remaining oxygen content due to biological or chemical consumption","Trapped pockets of still air that serve as insulation","Areas where no wind blows due to natural terrain features blocking airflow patterns","Spaces where radio signals and electronic communications cannot reach or penetrate","Air inside a sealed container that has become stale and potentially hazardous to breathe"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Dead air space refers to trapped, still air within insulation layers. Since still air is a poor heat conductor, these pockets significantly reduce heat transfer and improve insulation."},
{id:115,cat:"shelter",q:"How can you waterproof a debris shelter's roof?",o:["By using only large broad leaves arranged in a single flat layer across the top","Debris shelters cannot realistically be made waterproof regardless of technique or materials used","By packing mud only on the inside surfaces to create a sealed moisture barrier","By layering debris thickly at a steep angle so water runs off","By using only pine needles since their natural resin provides some inherent water resistance"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Layer debris thickly (2-3 feet of leaves, boughs, etc.) at a steep angle so water runs off. Start layering from the bottom up, like shingles, to shed water effectively."},
{id:116,cat:"shelter",q:"What is a wikiup shelter?",o:["A cone-shaped shelter built with poles and covered with brush or debris","A type of online encyclopedia entry about wilderness survival techniques and strategies","A permanent log cabin built using traditional frontier construction methods and materials","A shelter constructed from a single large overhanging rock or boulder formation","A military-style tent designed for rapid deployment in field operations"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"A wikiup is a cone-shaped (tipi-like) shelter made by arranging poles in a circle, tying them at the top, and covering the frame with available natural materials like bark, brush, and grass."},
{id:117,cat:"shelter",q:"What is the recommended angle for a lean-to shelter roof to effectively shed rain?",o:["Nearly flat at about 10 degrees to maximize the covered floor area underneath","90 degrees (fully vertical) to let rain slide off as quickly as physically possible","About 45 to 60 degrees","There is no recommended angle since any slope will eventually shed water with enough time","About 5 degrees, which provides the most usable interior headroom for occupants"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"A 45 to 60 degree angle effectively sheds rain and snow while still providing usable interior space. Too flat and water pools; too steep and you lose interior space."},
{id:118,cat:"shelter",q:"During a flood warning, why should you avoid basement shelter areas?",o:["Basements are always safe during floods because they are below the main structure","Basements have poor cell phone reception making it difficult to receive emergency alerts","Basements are typically too cold and uncomfortable for extended sheltering periods","There is no particular reason to avoid basements during flood conditions","Basements can flood rapidly, trapping occupants"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Basements can flood rapidly from rising water, sewer backups, or breached walls. Floodwater often contains sewage, chemicals, and debris, and trapped occupants can drown."},
{id:119,cat:"shelter",q:"What is a key consideration when sheltering in an abandoned building?",o:["Abandoned buildings are always structurally safe since they were originally built to code standards","Check for structural integrity, hazardous materials, and vermin","Abandoned buildings should be avoided entirely because they are always haunted or cursed","Check for WiFi signal only so you can contact emergency services through internet access","They are always better than being outdoors regardless of the building's actual condition or stability"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Inspect abandoned structures for structural stability, hazardous materials (asbestos, lead), unstable floors, vermin, and other dangers before using them as shelter."},
{id:120,cat:"shelter",q:"How can body heat alone raise the temperature in a small snow shelter?",o:["It cannot; snow shelters always remain at the same temperature as the outside ambient air","Only if there are more than 10 people packed tightly inside the shelter generating collective warmth","Body heat can raise the interior temperature to over 70°F, making it feel like a heated room","Body heat can raise the interior to near 32°F even in extreme cold","Body heat actually makes snow shelters colder because it causes melting that then refreezes into ice"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"The insulating properties of snow combined with body heat can maintain the interior of a small snow shelter near 32°F, which is significantly warmer than extreme outside temperatures."},
{id:121,cat:"shelter",q:"What is a 'safe room' as defined by FEMA?",o:["A reinforced room providing near-absolute tornado and severe wind protection","Any room in the house that has a functioning lock on the door for personal security","A bank vault or similar commercial-grade steel-reinforced financial storage facility","A room with no windows, regardless of its construction materials or structural reinforcement","Any basement area, whether finished or unfinished, in a residential building"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"A FEMA safe room is built to FEMA P-320 or ICC 500 standards, designed to withstand extreme winds and flying debris from tornadoes and hurricanes."},
{id:122,cat:"shelter",q:"When should you evacuate rather than shelter in place?",o:["Never; you should always shelter in place regardless of the type or severity of the emergency","Only if your house is completely and totally destroyed beyond any possible use as shelter","When authorities order evacuation, or when staying poses greater risk than leaving","Only during daytime hours when visibility allows for safe travel on potentially damaged roads","Only if you have a vehicle available, since evacuating on foot is never a viable option"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Evacuate when ordered by authorities, when staying puts you at greater risk (wildfire, major flooding, chemical spill moving toward you), or when your shelter is compromised."},
{id:123,cat:"shelter",q:"What should you do with your home's utilities before evacuating for a flood?",o:["Leave everything running so the house is ready for your return after the flood recedes","Lock all doors securely but leave all utilities on to prevent pipes from freezing during absence","Turn everything to maximum output so the systems are fully pressurized and operational","Only turn off the TV and other non-essential entertainment electronics to conserve energy","Turn off gas, electricity, and water at the mains if safe"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"If time permits and it is safe, turn off utilities at the main switches to prevent fires, electrocution from flood water contact, and gas leaks."},
{id:124,cat:"shelter",q:"What is a 'ridge shelter' or A-frame shelter?",o:["A shelter that can only be built on a mountain ridge or elevated terrain feature","A shelter shaped like the letter A with two sloping sides meeting at a ridge pole","A flat-roofed shelter designed to collect rainwater on its broad upper surface","A shelter built exclusively from corrugated metal sheets and industrial materials","A commercial tent brand that specializes in lightweight backpacking shelter systems"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"An A-frame shelter has two sloping sides meeting at a central ridgepole, creating a triangular cross-section. It sheds rain well and can be built with tarps or natural materials."},
{id:125,cat:"shelter",q:"How does a properly built fire pit enhance an emergency shelter?",o:["It only provides light and has no other practical survival function whatsoever","It is only useful for signaling aircraft and distant rescue teams during nighttime operations","It keeps all animals away permanently from the entire surrounding campsite area","It provides heat, cooking, water purification, and a morale boost","It has no meaningful benefit when placed near a shelter and can actually be a hazard"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"A fire pit near a shelter provides warmth, a means to cook food and purify water, a way to signal rescuers, and an important psychological boost for morale."},
{id:126,cat:"shelter",q:"What is the danger of sleeping directly on cold ground without insulation?",o:["Conductive heat loss can lead to hypothermia","You might get dirty, which could lead to skin irritation and minor discomfort over time","The ground is always comfortable enough to sleep on without any additional insulation layers","There is no real danger since the human body naturally adjusts to ground temperature overnight","You might sleep too long because the cool temperature promotes deeper and more extended sleep cycles"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"The ground conducts heat away from the body about 25 times faster than still air. Without insulation, conductive heat loss can quickly lead to hypothermia even in moderate temperatures."},
{id:127,cat:"shelter",q:"In an urban disaster, what common items can serve as improvised shelter materials?",o:["Only professional camping gear that has been specifically designed and rated for emergency use","Nothing in a city environment can realistically serve as adequate emergency shelter material","Cardboard, plastic sheeting, tarps, and large appliance boxes","Only metal objects such as dumpsters, car hoods, and sheet metal from damaged structures","Only fabric items like curtains, bedsheets, tablecloths, and clothing from nearby buildings"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"In urban settings, cardboard, plastic sheeting, tarps, large boxes, vehicle covers, and even overturned vehicles or dumpsters can provide emergency wind and rain protection."},
{id:128,cat:"shelter",q:"What is the recommended practice when using a candle for heat in an enclosed emergency shelter?",o:["Use as many candles as possible to maximize heat output and light throughout the enclosed space","Burn candles only during daytime hours when natural ventilation from open windows is available","Candles produce no meaningful heat and are only useful as a light source in emergencies","Place candles near plastic sheeting so the radiant heat warms the walls of the shelter","Use sparingly with ventilation and keep away from flammables"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Candles can provide modest heat and light but require ventilation to prevent carbon monoxide buildup, should never be left unattended, and must be kept away from flammable materials."},
{id:129,cat:"shelter",q:"What should you include in a shelter-in-place supply kit?",o:["Only water, since that is the single most critical resource for short-term sheltering in place","Water, food, medications, flashlight, radio, plastic sheeting, duct tape, and first aid supplies","Only a first aid kit, since medical emergencies are the primary concern during shelter-in-place events","A television and magazines to maintain morale and stay informed during the sheltering period","Only canned food since it has the longest shelf life and does not require refrigeration or preparation"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"A shelter-in-place kit should include water (1 gallon per person per day), food, medications, flashlight, batteries, battery-powered radio, plastic sheeting, duct tape, and a first aid kit."},
{id:130,cat:"shelter",q:"How long might you need to shelter in place during a chemical emergency?",o:["Only a few seconds before the chemical cloud fully disperses into the upper atmosphere","Exactly 24 hours, which is the standard protocol established by all emergency management agencies","At least one month to ensure all residual contamination has been completely neutralized","A few hours until the hazard passes or an all-clear is given","Only 10 minutes, after which any airborne chemical will have fully settled to ground level"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Chemical shelter-in-place is typically a short-term measure lasting a few hours. Stay sheltered until authorities issue an all-clear via radio, TV, or other official channels."},
{id:131,cat:"water",q:"How long can a person typically survive without water?",o:["About 3 days depending on conditions","About 30 days if the person remains stationary and conserves all physical energy","About 2 weeks as long as adequate food and shade are consistently available","About 1 hour before severe organ damage begins to occur from acute dehydration","Indefinitely if sufficient food is available since food contains enough moisture to sustain life"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Humans can typically survive about 3 days without water, though this varies with temperature, activity level, and individual health. Water is the highest survival priority after immediate safety."},
{id:132,cat:"water",q:"How much water should you store per person per day for emergency preparedness?",o:["1 cup, which is sufficient for minimal hydration during a sedentary shelter-in-place scenario","1 quart, which covers basic drinking needs for a moderately active adult in temperate conditions","At least 1 gallon","5 gallons to cover drinking, cooking, sanitation, and potential water-sharing with neighbors","Half a cup, supplemented by moisture from stored emergency food rations"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"FEMA recommends storing at least 1 gallon of water per person per day for drinking and sanitation, with a minimum 3-day supply for evacuations and 2-week supply for home."},
{id:133,cat:"water",q:"At what temperature should water be boiled to make it safe for drinking?",o:["Warm it to 100°F, which is enough to neutralize most common waterborne bacterial pathogens","Bring to 50°F, which activates the natural purification enzymes present in most freshwater sources","Heat to exactly 150°F and maintain that specific temperature for a minimum of twenty minutes","Boil for 30 minutes minimum to ensure complete elimination of all possible contaminants","Bring to a rolling boil for at least 1 minute (3 minutes above 6,500 feet)"],a:4,src:"CDC",exp:"The CDC recommends bringing water to a rolling boil for 1 minute (3 minutes at elevations above 6,500 feet) to kill bacteria, viruses, and parasites."},
{id:134,cat:"water",q:"Which water purification method is effective against viruses, bacteria, AND protozoa?",o:["A cotton cloth filter alone, which physically traps all three categories of waterborne pathogens","Boiling","Letting water sit in direct sunlight for approximately 10 minutes on a warm day","Straining through a standard paper coffee filter to remove all microscopic organisms","Adding sugar, which creates an osmotic environment hostile to pathogens"],a:1,src:"CDC",exp:"Boiling is one of the most reliable methods to kill all types of waterborne pathogens including viruses, bacteria, and protozoan cysts like Giardia and Cryptosporidium."},
{id:135,cat:"water",q:"How much regular unscented household bleach (5-9% sodium hypochlorite) should be added to 1 gallon of clear water for disinfection?",o:["1 cup, which provides a strong enough concentration to neutralize all pathogens rapidly","Half a bottle to ensure comprehensive disinfection of heavily contaminated water sources","1 tablespoon stirred thoroughly and allowed to react for at least fifteen minutes","8 drops (about 1/8 teaspoon)","No bleach should ever be used to treat drinking water under any circumstances whatsoever"],a:3,src:"EPA",exp:"Add 8 drops (about 1/8 teaspoon) of regular unscented household bleach (5-9% sodium hypochlorite) per gallon of clear water. Stir and let stand for 30 minutes before drinking."},
{id:136,cat:"water",q:"After adding bleach to water for purification, how long should you wait before drinking?",o:["Wait at least 30 minutes","Drink immediately since the bleach begins working on contact with waterborne pathogens","Wait 24 hours to allow complete chemical neutralization of all contaminants and full dissipation","Wait 1 week to ensure even the most resistant bacterial spores have been fully eliminated","Wait 5 seconds, just long enough to briefly stir the solution before consuming"],a:0,src:"EPA",exp:"After adding the correct amount of bleach, stir well and let the water stand for at least 30 minutes. The water should have a slight chlorine smell; if not, repeat the dosage and wait another 15 minutes."},
{id:137,cat:"water",q:"What type of household bleach should be used for emergency water purification?",o:["Scented bleach, which has additional antimicrobial essential oils that boost purification effectiveness","Color-safe bleach, which uses a gentler oxidizing agent that is safer for human consumption","Regular unscented liquid chlorine bleach with 5-9% sodium hypochlorite","Bleach with added cleaners or thickeners for enhanced pathogen elimination and improved water clarity","Powdered bleach dissolved in warm water first to create a concentrated stock purification solution"],a:2,src:"EPA",exp:"Use only regular, unscented liquid chlorine bleach containing 5-9% sodium hypochlorite. Scented bleach, color-safe bleach, and bleach with added cleaners contain chemicals unsafe for consumption."},
{id:138,cat:"water",q:"What is the main limitation of most portable water filters?",o:["They cannot remove any contaminants whatsoever and are essentially just marketing products","They work too slowly to be practical for producing enough drinking water for even one person","They remove too many beneficial minerals that the body needs for proper hydration and health","They make water taste noticeably bad due to the activated carbon and ceramic filter elements","Most do not remove viruses, which are too small for the filter media"],a:4,src:"CDC",exp:"Most portable water filters effectively remove bacteria and protozoa but cannot remove viruses due to their extremely small size. A purifier or chemical treatment is needed for viruses."},
{id:139,cat:"water",q:"What does 'turbid' water mean, and why does it affect water treatment?",o:["It means the water is safe to drink because turbidity indicates a high concentration of natural minerals","It means the water is cloudy with suspended particles that can shield pathogens from treatment","It means the water is cold, which significantly slows down the chemical reactions needed for disinfection","It means the water has a high mineral content, making chemical treatment methods less effective overall","It means the water is flowing rapidly, which introduces excess oxygen that neutralizes disinfectants"],a:1,src:"EPA",exp:"Turbid water is cloudy with suspended particles that can harbor and shield pathogens from chemical disinfection and UV treatment. Pre-filter turbid water through cloth before treatment."},
{id:140,cat:"water",q:"If water is turbid before treating with bleach, what should you do?",o:["Use less bleach than normal since the sediment particles already have natural antibacterial properties","Add salt instead of bleach because salt is more effective at treating water with high particulate content","Do not treat it; find completely clear water since no amount of chemical treatment can purify turbid water","Double the bleach (16 drops per gallon) or pre-filter first","Freeze it first to separate the sediment from the clean water through the crystallization process"],a:3,src:"EPA",exp:"For turbid water, either pre-filter through clean cloth to remove sediment, or double the bleach dosage to 16 drops per gallon. Let stand for 30 minutes before drinking."},
{id:141,cat:"water",q:"What is SODIS (Solar Water Disinfection)?",o:["A method using sunlight UV-A to disinfect water in clear PET bottles over 6+ hours","A commercial water filter brand specializing in portable gravity-fed purification systems","A chemical water treatment tablet containing chlorine dioxide for field water purification","A type of deep water well that uses solar-powered pumps to extract groundwater","An industrial water treatment plant process used by municipal water systems worldwide"],a:0,src:"WHO",exp:"SODIS involves filling clear PET bottles with water and exposing them to direct sunlight for at least 6 hours (2 days if cloudy). UV-A radiation and heat inactivate pathogens."},
{id:142,cat:"water",q:"What are the early signs of dehydration?",o:["Excessive sweating and intense hunger pangs that increase progressively over several hours","Cold hands and feet only, with no other noticeable symptoms until severe dehydration sets in","Thirst, dark yellow urine, dry mouth, fatigue, and dizziness","Increased appetite and cravings for salty foods as the body attempts to retain water","Blurred vision only, which is the earliest and most reliable clinical indicator of fluid deficit"],a:2,src:"CDC",exp:"Early dehydration signs include thirst, dark-colored urine, dry mouth, tiredness, dizziness, and decreased urine output. Severe dehydration can be life-threatening."},
{id:143,cat:"water",q:"What color should urine be to indicate proper hydration?",o:["Dark brown, which indicates a healthy concentration of waste products being efficiently processed","Dark amber, showing that the kidneys are properly conserving water and filtering at optimal levels","Completely clear and colorless at all times, which is the only reliable indicator of true adequate hydration","Bright orange, which indicates optimal levels of B vitamins and proper kidney function","Pale yellow or straw-colored"],a:4,src:"CDC",exp:"Pale yellow or straw-colored urine generally indicates adequate hydration. Dark yellow or amber urine suggests dehydration, while consistently clear urine may indicate overhydration."},
{id:144,cat:"water",q:"Which water source is generally safest for emergency collection in the wild?",o:["Standing puddles that have been undisturbed for several days allowing sediment to settle naturally","Fast-flowing streams or springs from the ground","Water from ponds with visible algae, which indicates a thriving aquatic ecosystem and biological activity","Water near agricultural runoff areas since the soil naturally filters contaminants from farming operations","Water downstream from a campsite where previous occupants may have already tested and used the source"],a:1,src:"EPA",exp:"Fast-flowing water from streams or natural springs is generally safer than standing water, though all wild water should still be treated before drinking. Flowing water has less bacterial growth."},
{id:145,cat:"water",q:"How can you collect water from vegetation through transpiration?",o:["Cut down the entire tree and extract moisture from the inner sapwood and cambium layers","Burn the vegetation and collect the steam using a makeshift condensation apparatus overhead","Squeeze the leaves firmly by hand to extract the moisture stored inside the leaf cell structures","Tie a clear plastic bag around a leafy branch in sunlight","Soak the leaves in salt water to trigger reverse osmosis and release their internal moisture content"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Tying a clear plastic bag around a leafy branch traps moisture released through transpiration. Over several hours in sunlight, a usable amount of water can collect in the bag's lowest point."},
{id:146,cat:"water",q:"What is a solar still and how does it work?",o:["A ground hole covered with clear plastic that condenses moisture using solar heat","A device that uses photovoltaic solar panels to electrically pump water from underground sources","A type of insulated water bottle designed to keep water cold using vacuum-sealed solar-reflective walls","A commercial distillery that uses concentrated solar thermal energy for large-scale water purification","A rain collection system that channels rooftop runoff into covered food-grade storage barrels"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"A solar still uses a hole dug in moist ground, covered with clear plastic weighted in the center. Solar heat evaporates ground moisture, which condenses on the plastic and drips into a collection container."},
{id:147,cat:"water",q:"Why should you avoid drinking saltwater in a survival situation?",o:["It tastes bad and will likely cause you to vomit, wasting precious energy and stomach contents","It has no calories and therefore provides no nutritional value to a person in a survival scenario","Your kidneys need more water to process the excess salt, worsening dehydration","It causes sunburn by increasing skin sensitivity to ultraviolet radiation from sun exposure","It is always contaminated with harmful bacteria and marine parasites that cause severe gastrointestinal illness"],a:2,src:"CDC",exp:"Drinking saltwater accelerates dehydration because your kidneys require more water to flush out the excess salt than the amount of water you consumed, creating a net water loss."},
{id:148,cat:"water",q:"What is the proper way to store emergency water in containers at home?",o:["In any container including used milk jugs, which are convenient, widely available, and perfectly adequate","In the freezer only, since freezing eliminates all potential bacterial growth and keeps water indefinitely pure","In open buckets placed throughout the house for easy access during an emergency situation","In containers previously used for household chemicals, as long as they have been rinsed once with tap water","In food-grade containers, cleaned and sanitized, stored cool and dark"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Store water in clean, food-grade containers with tight lids. Sanitize containers with diluted bleach before filling. Store in a cool, dark place and replace every 6 months."},
{id:149,cat:"water",q:"How long can commercially bottled water be stored for emergency use?",o:["Only 1 week before it becomes unsafe to drink due to plastic chemical leaching into the water","Indefinitely if stored properly, though check the best-by date for taste","Exactly 30 days from the date of purchase, after which the manufacturer warranty for safety expires","Only 1 year maximum before the FDA requires it to be discarded and replaced with a fresh supply","It expires within 24 hours after purchase once the factory seal and protective packaging are broken"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Commercially bottled water has an indefinite shelf life if stored properly in a cool, dark place. Best-by dates are for taste quality, not safety, but rotating stock is still recommended."},
{id:150,cat:"water",q:"What household water sources can be used in an emergency if the water supply is cut off?",o:["Toilet bowl water, which is technically treated municipal water and safe if the bowl is clean","Waterbed water, since it is essentially sealed and protected from external contamination sources","Swimming pool water for drinking, as the chlorine already present makes it safe for consumption","Water heater tank and melted ice cubes from the freezer","Radiator fluid, which contains water mixed with antifreeze that can be separated through simple filtering"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Your water heater tank can hold 30-80 gallons of drinkable water. Melted ice cubes are also safe. Avoid toilet bowl water, pool water (chemicals), waterbed water (chemicals), and radiator fluid."},
{id:151,cat:"water",q:"How do you safely drain water from a home water heater for emergency use?",o:["Turn off the water supply and power/gas, open the drain valve, and let air in through a faucet","Break the tank open with a heavy tool or sledgehammer to access the water inside","Shake the water heater back and forth vigorously until water comes out","Remove the top completely and scoop out the water with a bucket","Cut the pipes with a saw and catch the water as it drains"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Turn off the power/gas and water supply to the heater. Open a hot water faucet in the house to let air in, then open the drain valve at the bottom of the tank to collect water."},
{id:152,cat:"water",q:"What is the primary risk of drinking untreated water from a seemingly clean stream?",o:["It is always perfectly safe because flowing water naturally purifies itself over time","It will taste bad due to high concentrations of dissolved organic compounds and tannins","Invisible pathogens like Giardia, Cryptosporidium, bacteria, and viruses","It contains far too many minerals and heavy metals for safe human consumption","There is no risk from flowing water since movement kills harmful organisms"],a:2,src:"CDC",exp:"Even clear-looking water can contain harmful pathogens including Giardia, Cryptosporidium, E. coli, and viruses. Animals and upstream contamination can introduce pathogens invisible to the naked eye."},
{id:153,cat:"water",q:"What is iodine water treatment and when should it NOT be used?",o:["Iodine is a food supplement only, commonly added to table salt for nutritional purposes","Iodine is only for wound treatment and should never be ingested under any circumstances","Iodine makes water taste better by neutralizing sulfur compounds and dissolved minerals","Iodine should not be used by anyone ever because it is classified as a toxic substance","It disinfects water but should not be used by pregnant women, those with thyroid conditions, or iodine-allergic individuals"],a:4,src:"CDC",exp:"Iodine tablets or liquid can disinfect water but should not be used by pregnant women, people with thyroid conditions, or those with iodine allergies. It is also not recommended for long-term use."},
{id:154,cat:"water",q:"What is the minimum amount of water an adult needs per day for survival in moderate conditions?",o:["About 1 cup, which is sufficient if you minimize all physical movement and rest in shade","About 2 liters (half a gallon) minimum for drinking","About 5 gallons to account for drinking, cooking, and basic sanitation needs","About 1 tablespoon, as the body can extract moisture from food to compensate","About 10 liters per day at a minimum regardless of temperature or activity level"],a:1,src:"CDC",exp:"An adult needs a minimum of about 2 liters (half a gallon) of water per day for basic survival in temperate conditions, though more is needed in hot weather or during physical exertion."},
{id:155,cat:"water",q:"Why should you avoid eating snow for hydration in a winter survival situation?",o:["Snow contains no water molecules that the human body can actually absorb or utilize","Snow causes severe and irreversible tooth damage due to the extreme cold temperature","Snow is always contaminated with atmospheric pollutants, bacteria, and industrial particulates","Eating snow lowers body temperature and accelerates hypothermia","Snow is high in calories and will make you feel full without providing actual hydration"],a:3,src:"CDC",exp:"Eating snow lowers core body temperature and requires your body to expend energy (calories) to melt it, which can accelerate hypothermia. Melt snow first using fire or body heat in a container."},
{id:156,cat:"water",q:"What is a gravity-fed water filter system?",o:["A system using gravity to pull water through a filter element without pumping or power","A filter that uses an electric pump to force water through multiple purification stages at high pressure","A filter that only works in the microgravity environment of space stations and spacecraft","A chemical treatment system that relies on dissolved chlorine tablets and settling agents","A UV light system that uses solar-powered ultraviolet radiation to sterilize water in clear bottles"],a:0,src:"EPA",exp:"Gravity-fed filters use the natural force of gravity to move water through a filter element from an upper chamber to a lower collection chamber. No pumping, electricity, or batteries needed."},
{id:157,cat:"water",q:"What does a 0.2 micron filter rating mean for water filtration?",o:["It removes only particles that are visible to the naked eye, such as sand, leaves, and large sediment","It removes only sand, gravel, and other coarse debris while allowing everything else to pass through","It can remove most bacteria and protozoa but not viruses","It removes everything including dissolved minerals, salts, and all microscopic organisms completely","It is a standardized measure of water flow rate expressed in liters per minute per square inch"],a:2,src:"CDC",exp:"A 0.2 micron (absolute) filter can remove bacteria and protozoan cysts but not most viruses, which are typically 0.02 to 0.3 microns. For virus removal, a purifier or chemical treatment is needed."},
{id:158,cat:"water",q:"What chemical can be used as an alternative to bleach for water purification in emergencies?",o:["Rubbing alcohol, which kills bacteria on contact when added to drinking water in small quantities","Hydrogen peroxide for drinking water, commonly used at a ratio of two drops per liter","Baking soda dissolved in water to raise pH and neutralize acidic contaminants and pathogens","Vinegar, which has natural antimicrobial properties effective against waterborne illness","Chlorine dioxide tablets or drops"],a:4,src:"EPA",exp:"Chlorine dioxide tablets or drops (like Aquamira or Potable Aqua ClO2) are effective water purification chemicals that kill bacteria, viruses, and protozoa including Cryptosporidium."},
{id:159,cat:"water",q:"How can you tell if a natural water source may be contaminated?",o:["Contaminated water always looks visibly dirty, discolored, or cloudy, so clear water is always safe to drink","Look for dead animals nearby, algae blooms, foul odors, chemical sheens, or lack of vegetation","If it is flowing quickly over rocks, it is always safe because the movement aerates and purifies it","If animals drink from it, it is safe for humans since animals have the same vulnerability to pathogens","Only laboratory testing conducted by certified professionals can reliably detect contamination"],a:1,src:"EPA",exp:"Warning signs include dead animals, blue-green algae, foam or chemical sheen on the surface, unusual odors, discolored water, and dead or absent vegetation along the water's edge."},
{id:160,cat:"water",q:"What is a water pre-filter and why is it used?",o:["It is a decorative water feature designed for ornamental garden ponds and fountains","It removes all pathogens including bacteria, viruses, protozoa, and chemical contaminants from water","It is the only filtration step needed because it handles both particles and microorganisms","A coarse filter used to remove large debris before primary treatment, extending filter life","It is a chemical additive that causes sediment particles to clump together and settle out of water"],a:3,src:"EPA",exp:"A pre-filter removes large particles, sediment, and debris before the water goes through the primary treatment method, which helps prevent clogging and extends the life of finer filters."},
{id:161,cat:"water",q:"What is the advantage of UV water purification (such as a SteriPEN)?",o:["It kills bacteria, viruses, and protozoa quickly without chemicals or bad taste","It removes sediment, dissolved chemicals, heavy metals, and particulate matter from the water","It makes water noticeably colder, which improves taste and helps preserve it for longer storage","It adds beneficial minerals like calcium and magnesium to otherwise mineral-depleted water","It works without any power source whatsoever, making it ideal for extended wilderness situations"],a:0,src:"CDC",exp:"UV purification disrupts the DNA of microorganisms, effectively killing bacteria, viruses, and protozoa in about 60-90 seconds without affecting taste or adding chemicals. Requires batteries or power."},
{id:162,cat:"water",q:"How can dew be collected for drinking water?",o:["Only with specialized commercial dew-harvesting equipment designed for arid climate research stations","Dew cannot be collected in usable amounts since it evaporates far too quickly to gather meaningfully","Drag absorbent cloth through grass in early morning, then wring it into a container","Wait for it to pool naturally in large puddles on flat impermeable surfaces like parking lots or rocks","Use a battery-powered vacuum device specifically engineered for atmospheric moisture extraction"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"In the early morning, drag absorbent cloth through dew-covered grass or tie cloths to your ankles while walking. Wring the water into a container. This can yield surprising amounts."},
{id:163,cat:"water",q:"What is the danger of drinking water from a source with blue-green algae?",o:["It will permanently dye your skin, teeth, and internal organs a noticeable blue-green color","Blue-green algae is beneficial to drink because it is rich in protein, vitamins, and antioxidants","It tastes slightly sweet but is otherwise completely safe for consumption by healthy adults","It only causes minor stomach upset that resolves within an hour or two without treatment","Blue-green algae (cyanobacteria) can produce toxins causing liver damage, neurological effects, and death"],a:4,src:"EPA",exp:"Cyanobacterial blooms (blue-green algae) can produce potent toxins (cyanotoxins) that are not removed by boiling and can cause severe liver damage, neurological damage, and death."},
{id:164,cat:"water",q:"What is a rain catchment system?",o:["A system designed for catching clouds using large elevated nets strung between tall poles on mountaintops","A setup that collects, channels, and stores rainwater from surfaces like roofs for later use","A drainage system engineered specifically to move water away from buildings and prevent flooding","A commercial irrigation system only available to licensed agricultural operations and large farms","A type of decorative guttering installed for aesthetic purposes on historic buildings and cottages"],a:1,src:"EPA",exp:"Rain catchment systems use clean collection surfaces (like a tarp or clean roof), gutters, and downspouts to channel rainwater into storage containers for emergency use."},
{id:165,cat:"water",q:"When collecting rainwater for drinking in an emergency, what is the best practice?",o:["Collect it from any available surface regardless of material, age, or previous contamination exposure","Collect from road surfaces for maximum volume since asphalt channels water efficiently into drains","Rainwater is always pure and needs absolutely no treatment because it has been naturally distilled","Let the first rain wash the collection surface, then begin collecting, and treat before drinking","Only collect during thunderstorms because the electrical activity in the atmosphere sterilizes rainwater"],a:3,src:"EPA",exp:"Let initial rain flush contaminants from collection surfaces before gathering water. Use clean collection surfaces and containers. Treat collected rainwater before drinking as it can contain contaminants."},
{id:166,cat:"water",q:"How should water purification tablets be stored to maintain effectiveness?",o:["In a cool, dry place in their original sealed container, away from heat and moisture","In direct sunlight to keep them warm, which activates and strengthens the chemical compounds","In a wet location to keep them ready for immediate dissolution when you need to use them","It does not matter how they are stored because the active chemical ingredients are completely stable","In the freezer at sub-zero temperatures to preserve maximum chemical potency over the long term"],a:0,src:"EPA",exp:"Water purification tablets should be kept in their original sealed container in a cool, dry place. Heat, moisture, and sunlight can degrade the active ingredients and reduce effectiveness."},
{id:167,cat:"water",q:"What happens to water purification effectiveness at very cold temperatures?",o:["Cold water is always sterile since bacteria and viruses cannot survive in low-temperature environments","Cold water actually purifies faster because pathogens are weakened and more vulnerable to chemicals","Chemical purification takes longer in cold water; you may need to double wait time or dosage","Temperature has absolutely no measurable effect on the speed or thoroughness of chemical purification","Chemicals do not dissolve in cold water at all, making chemical purification completely impossible below 40°F"],a:2,src:"CDC",exp:"Chemical disinfectants like chlorine and iodine work more slowly in cold water. Double the contact time or use a slightly higher dose when treating very cold water."},
{id:168,cat:"water",q:"How much water does a person need in hot weather or during strenuous activity?",o:["The same as in cool weather (2 liters), since the body's needs remain constant regardless of conditions","About 0.5 liters per day, because the body becomes more efficient at retaining water during exertion","Only 1 cup more than normal, which compensates sufficiently for additional perspiration losses","Less water is needed because sweating cools the body and reduces overall metabolic water demand","Up to 1 gallon (4 liters) or more per day"],a:4,src:"CDC",exp:"In hot weather or during physical exertion, water needs can double or triple to 1 gallon (4 liters) or more per day due to increased sweating and respiration."},
{id:169,cat:"water",q:"What is the risk of drinking flood water?",o:["Flood water is essentially clean rainwater that has simply accumulated in low-lying areas during storms","Flood water is contaminated with sewage, chemicals, animal waste, and debris — never drink it untreated","Flood water is safe after it sits undisturbed for an hour, allowing contaminants to settle to the bottom","Flood water only contains mud and dissolved soil particles, which are harmless when consumed","There is no risk if the water looks clear, since visible clarity indicates the absence of harmful pathogens"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Floodwater is highly contaminated with sewage, chemicals, petroleum products, pesticides, animal waste, and harmful microorganisms. It should never be consumed even after treatment."},
{id:170,cat:"water",q:"In a water emergency, which beverages can supplement your water supply?",o:["Alcoholic beverages like beer and wine, which contain enough water to offset their dehydrating effects","Energy drinks and coffee only, because their high caffeine content helps maintain alertness and focus","Only distilled water counts as a true supplement, since other beverages contain too many impurities","Fruit juices, milk, and other non-caffeinated, non-alcoholic beverages from your pantry","Saltwater mixed with sugar to create an electrolyte solution that mimics commercial sports drinks"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Canned fruit juices, non-caffeinated drinks, and other stored beverages can supplement water. Avoid alcohol (causes dehydration) and limit high-caffeine drinks (mild diuretic effect)."},
{id:171,cat:"water",q:"How can you make a basic improvised water filter in the wilderness?",o:["Layer charcoal, sand, and gravel in a container with a hole at the bottom and pour water through","You cannot filter water without commercial equipment specifically manufactured for that purpose","Just strain water through a t-shirt, which removes all harmful bacteria, viruses, and protozoa effectively","Shake the water vigorously for several minutes to oxygenate it and kill anaerobic pathogens","Add lemon juice to neutralize contaminants through its natural antibacterial citric acid properties"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Layer charcoal (from a campfire), fine sand, and gravel in a container with a drainage hole. Water passes through each layer, removing progressively finer particles. Still treat the water after filtering."},
{id:172,cat:"water",q:"What should you do with water containers that previously held non-food substances?",o:["Wash them thoroughly with soap and hot water several times and then they are perfectly safe to use","Rinse once with clean water and they are safe for immediate use storing drinking water supplies","Never use them for drinking water as chemicals can leach in even after washing","They are fine for water storage after a thorough bleaching and sanitization process with dilute chlorine","Use them for hot water only, since heat prevents chemical residues from dissolving into the water"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Never use containers that held chemicals, bleach (as a product), pesticides, or other non-food substances for water storage. Chemicals can leach into water even after thorough washing."},
{id:173,cat:"water",q:"What is the boiling point of water at sea level?",o:["100°F (38°C)","180°F (82°C)","150°F (66°C)","250°F (121°C)","212°F (100°C)"],a:4,src:"CDC",exp:"Water boils at 212°F (100°C) at sea level. At higher elevations, the boiling point decreases due to lower atmospheric pressure, which is why longer boiling times are needed at altitude."},
{id:174,cat:"water",q:"Why does water need to be boiled longer at higher elevations?",o:["Water is significantly colder at high elevations due to lower ambient air temperatures year-round","Water boils at a lower temperature at altitude due to reduced pressure, requiring longer boiling","Pathogens are biologically stronger and more heat-resistant at altitude due to UV adaptation","Water evaporates faster at altitude, so you need to boil longer to retain enough volume for drinking","It does not; boiling time is exactly the same everywhere regardless of elevation or atmospheric conditions"],a:1,src:"CDC",exp:"At higher elevations, reduced atmospheric pressure lowers the boiling point. Water boils at lower temperatures that may not be sufficient for quick pathogen kill, so boil for 3 minutes above 6,500 feet."},
{id:175,cat:"water",q:"How should you handle water containers during and after a boil water advisory?",o:["No special handling is needed since the municipal water system flushes itself automatically once the advisory ends","Heat all containers in the oven at 200°F for thirty minutes to sterilize them before refilling with tap water","Only rinse containers with cold water because hot water can damage plastic and leach harmful chemicals","Disinfect container lids and openings, flush water lines, and discard ice made during the advisory","Replace all containers in the house with brand new ones purchased from a store after the advisory is lifted"],a:3,src:"EPA",exp:"When a boil water advisory is lifted, flush water lines, disinfect container surfaces that contact water, discard ice made during the advisory, and run water softeners through a regeneration cycle."},
{id:176,cat:"food",q:"How long can most perishable foods safely remain without refrigeration (above 40°F)?",o:["No more than 2 hours (1 hour if above 90°F)","Up to 24 hours if the food is kept covered and out of direct sunlight in a climate-controlled room","Up to 1 week as long as the food is stored in airtight containers with ice packs nearby","Indefinitely if kept in shade, since temperatures below ambient rarely enter the pathogen danger zone","About 12 hours for most items, though dairy products and raw meats spoil somewhat more quickly"],a:0,src:"USDA",exp:"The USDA's 2-hour rule states perishable food should not be left out above 40°F for more than 2 hours, reduced to 1 hour if the ambient temperature exceeds 90°F."},
{id:177,cat:"food",q:"What is the ideal temperature range for a refrigerator to safely store food?",o:["50-60°F (10-16°C)","25-30°F (-4 to -1°C)","35-40°F (1.7-4.4°C)","45-50°F (7-10°C)","60-65°F (16-18°C)"],a:2,src:"USDA",exp:"The USDA recommends keeping refrigerators at or below 40°F (4°C). The range of 35-40°F keeps food safely cold without freezing most items."},
{id:178,cat:"food",q:"During a power outage, how long will food in a full freezer stay frozen?",o:["About 2 hours before items begin thawing significantly, even with the door completely sealed shut","Indefinitely, because the insulation in modern freezers is sufficient to maintain safe temperatures","About 1 week if you wrap the freezer in blankets and place it in the coldest room of the house","Only 30 minutes, after which all frozen items must be cooked or discarded immediately for safety","About 48 hours if the door is kept closed"],a:4,src:"USDA",exp:"A full freezer will keep food frozen for approximately 48 hours (24 hours if half full) if the door remains closed. Avoid opening the freezer door unnecessarily during an outage."},
{id:179,cat:"food",q:"Which emergency food supplies have the longest shelf life?",o:["Fresh fruits and vegetables stored in a root cellar with consistent temperature and humidity control","Freeze-dried foods, white rice, dried beans, honey, and salt","Bread and dairy products that have been vacuum-sealed and stored in temperature-controlled environments","Canned meats only, because the hermetic seal and high sodium content prevent all bacterial growth","Eggs and cheese when properly coated in mineral oil and wax to create an airtight protective barrier"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Freeze-dried foods (25-30 years), white rice (30+ years), dried beans (30+ years), honey (indefinite), sugar, and salt have the longest shelf lives when stored properly."},
{id:180,cat:"food",q:"How should canned food be stored for maximum shelf life?",o:["In direct sunlight, which helps maintain consistent internal temperature and prevents moisture buildup","In a hot garage where temperatures stay above 80°F to keep the contents properly sterilized","In the freezer to extend shelf life by slowing all bacterial and chemical degradation processes","In a cool, dark, dry place between 50-70°F","Near a heat source like a furnace to prevent the cans from developing condensation and rust"],a:3,src:"USDA",exp:"Store canned goods in a cool, dark, dry location at 50-70°F. High temperatures reduce shelf life and quality. Most commercially canned foods are safe for 2-5 years if the can is undamaged."},
{id:181,cat:"food",q:"What are the signs that canned food has gone bad and should not be eaten?",o:["Bulging, leaking, or severely dented cans; foul odor; spurting liquid; or mold","The can is slightly dusty on top, indicating it has been sitting on the shelf for a very long time","The label is faded or discolored from prolonged exposure to light, humidity, or temperature changes","The can feels cold to the touch, suggesting that internal chemical reactions have altered the contents","The printed expiration date is one day past, which legally requires immediate disposal of the product"],a:0,src:"USDA",exp:"Discard canned food if the can is bulging, leaking, severely dented (especially on seams), or rusted through. Also discard if the contents smell foul, spurt when opened, or show mold."},
{id:182,cat:"food",q:"What is the 'danger zone' temperature range for food safety?",o:["0-32°F (-18 to 0°C)","200-212°F (93-100°C)","40-140°F (4-60°C)","Below 0°F (-18°C)","150-200°F (66-93°C)"],a:2,src:"USDA",exp:"The danger zone is 40-140°F (4-60°C), where bacteria multiply rapidly. Perishable food should not remain in this temperature range for more than 2 hours."},
{id:183,cat:"food",q:"What is the safest way to thaw frozen food during a power outage?",o:["Leave it on the counter at room temperature, which thaws food evenly and prevents cold spots","Use a hair dryer set to low heat, directing warm air slowly and evenly across the frozen surface","Thaw in hot water to speed up the process and bring the food to a safe cooking temperature faster","Place it in direct sunlight near a window where solar heat will gently and naturally defrost the food","Keep it in the closed freezer as long as possible; if thawed, use cold water or cook immediately"],a:4,src:"USDA",exp:"Keep the freezer door closed as long as possible. If food has thawed but is still at 40°F or below with ice crystals, it can be safely refrozen or cooked. Never thaw at room temperature."},
{id:184,cat:"food",q:"In an emergency, which foods should you eat first from your pantry?",o:["Canned goods with the longest shelf life, so you can test their quality while other options are still available","Perishable foods and refrigerator items first, then freezer items, then shelf-stable pantry items","Only freeze-dried meals because they provide the most balanced and complete nutrition per serving","Only snack foods like chips, crackers, and cookies, which provide quick energy and require no preparation","Only water and juice to stay hydrated, since solid food is not necessary for the first several days"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Eat perishable foods first (fresh items, then refrigerated, then frozen) before they spoil, saving shelf-stable canned and dried foods for later when other options are exhausted."},
{id:185,cat:"food",q:"How many calories per day does an average adult need during an emergency situation?",o:["500 calories, which is sufficient when physical activity is kept to an absolute minimum during sheltering","100 calories per day, since the body enters a conservation mode during high-stress emergency situations","5,000 calories minimum to account for the increased metabolic demands of stress and emergency labor","At least 1,200 to 2,000 calories minimum, depending on activity level","Calories are not needed during emergencies because adrenaline provides all the energy the body requires"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"An average adult needs at least 1,200-2,000 calories per day as a minimum for basic functioning during an emergency. Higher activity levels, cold weather, and stress increase caloric needs."},
{id:186,cat:"food",q:"What is the primary nutritional concern during a prolonged emergency?",o:["Adequate caloric intake, safe water, and essential nutrients including vitamins and minerals","Not enough flavor variety, which causes appetite fatigue and significant psychological distress over time","Having too much food, which leads to waste management problems and attracts pests and wildlife","Only protein intake matters because it is the sole macronutrient required for tissue repair and survival","Only sugar intake matters because glucose is the brain's exclusive fuel source during stressful situations"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Maintaining adequate calories, hydration, and essential nutrients is critical. Include foods with protein, complex carbohydrates, fats, and vitamins/minerals in your emergency food supply."},
{id:187,cat:"food",q:"Why is it important to include comfort foods in an emergency food supply?",o:["They are the most nutritious option available, providing superior vitamin and mineral content per calorie","They have the longest shelf life of any food category due to high sugar and preservative content","Familiar comfort foods reduce stress and maintain morale, which is critical in emergencies","They require absolutely no preparation, cooking, or utensils, making them the most practical choice","They are the cheapest option per calorie, which makes them the most cost-effective for bulk storage"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"FEMA recommends including comfort foods because they reduce stress, maintain morale, and provide a sense of normalcy. This is especially important for children during emergencies."},
{id:188,cat:"food",q:"What cooking method is safest for use during a power outage inside the home?",o:["Charcoal grill inside the kitchen, which provides consistent heat and is easy to regulate for even cooking","A camp stove in the living room, positioned near an open window to allow adequate cross-ventilation","Burning wood in the fireplace to cook on, using a cast iron grate and heavy-duty pots over the flames","Generator-powered stove in a closed room, with the generator placed in the corner furthest from cooking","Canned heat (Sterno) with proper ventilation, or eat foods that do not require cooking"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Never use charcoal grills, camp stoves, or generators indoors due to carbon monoxide risk. Use canned heat (Sterno) with adequate ventilation, or consume foods that do not need cooking."},
{id:189,cat:"food",q:"Which common emergency food requires no cooking and has a long shelf life?",o:["Raw chicken stored at room temperature in a sealed container with salt packing for preservation","Peanut butter","Fresh fish that has been air-dried and salt-cured using traditional preserving methods","Raw eggs coated in mineral oil to seal the shell pores and prevent bacterial contamination","Uncooked rice, which must be soaked overnight but technically does not require heating to consume"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Peanut butter is an excellent emergency food: it requires no cooking, is calorie-dense, provides protein and fat, and has a long shelf life (up to a year or more)."},
{id:190,cat:"food",q:"How should you handle food safety when your home has been flooded?",o:["Wash flooded food thoroughly with soap and clean water, then cook at high temperatures to sterilize it","Flooded food is safe after drying it completely in the sun for several hours to eliminate moisture","Only discard fresh produce, but keep all packaged and sealed items since their containers protect them","Discard all food that contacted floodwater, including home-canned goods and screw-top or pull-top containers","Freeze all flooded food immediately to kill bacteria, then thaw and inspect before consuming normally"],a:3,src:"USDA",exp:"Discard all food that contacted floodwater except undamaged commercially canned goods (not pull-top). Flood water contains sewage, chemicals, and pathogens that penetrate most packaging."},
{id:191,cat:"food",q:"What types of commercially canned food can be saved after flooding?",o:["Only undamaged all-metal cans and retort pouches, after thorough exterior sanitization","All canned foods regardless of condition, since the factory seal protects contents from all contamination","None whatsoever; all canned goods must be discarded because floodwater compromises every type of seal","Only cans with paper labels intact, which indicates the seal was not breached by floodwater pressure","Only glass jars with metal lids, since glass is impermeable and cannot absorb floodwater contaminants"],a:0,src:"USDA",exp:"Undamaged all-metal cans (not dented, swollen, or rusted) can be saved. Remove labels, wash, and sanitize cans in a bleach solution before opening. Discard pull-top, screw-top, and damaged cans."},
{id:192,cat:"food",q:"What is the FIFO method for emergency food storage?",o:["Frozen Items, Fresh Options — a system prioritizing frozen foods over fresh ones in meal planning","First In, Forever Out — meaning stored food should never actually be consumed, only kept as backup","First In, First Out — rotate stock by using oldest items first","Fast Intake, Full Output — eat as much as possible before food expires to minimize waste","A brand name for a commercially available emergency food storage product and subscription service"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"FIFO (First In, First Out) means placing new supplies at the back and using older items first. This ensures food is consumed before expiration and maintains a fresh emergency supply."},
{id:193,cat:"food",q:"What is an MRE (Meal Ready to Eat)?",o:["A restaurant menu category designating pre-prepared entrees that can be served without additional cooking","A cooking method that involves rapid heating of ingredients in specially designed pressure containers","A meal that must be eaten raw because the packaging process eliminates the need for any heat treatment","A type of freeze-dried coffee designed for military field operations and long-duration camping trips","A self-contained military-grade meal with a long shelf life (3-5 years), requiring no cooking"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"MREs are complete meals used by the military, containing an entree, side, dessert, and often a flameless heater. They last 3-5 years at moderate temperatures and require no preparation."},
{id:194,cat:"food",q:"Why should you avoid eating large amounts of protein when water is scarce?",o:["Protein is not important and has no meaningful role in survival nutrition or bodily functions","Protein metabolism requires extra water for kidneys to process nitrogen waste, increasing dehydration","Protein frequently causes severe allergic reactions when consumed in survival situations under stress","Protein is always contaminated with harmful bacteria unless it has been commercially processed and sealed","Protein rapidly reduces core body temperature by diverting blood flow away from extremities during digestion"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Digesting protein produces nitrogen waste (urea) that requires additional water for kidney excretion. When water is limited, high protein intake accelerates dehydration."},
{id:195,cat:"food",q:"At what internal temperature should you cook poultry to ensure food safety?",o:["120°F (49°C)","145°F (63°C)","200°F (93°C)","165°F (74°C)","100°F (38°C)"],a:3,src:"USDA",exp:"All poultry (chicken, turkey, duck) must reach an internal temperature of 165°F (74°C) to kill harmful bacteria like Salmonella. Use a food thermometer to verify."},
{id:196,cat:"food",q:"What internal temperature is safe for ground meats (beef, pork, lamb)?",o:["160°F (71°C)","145°F (63°C)","125°F (52°C)","200°F (93°C)","100°F (38°C)"],a:0,src:"USDA",exp:"Ground meats should be cooked to an internal temperature of 160°F (71°C). Whole cuts of beef, pork, and lamb require a minimum of 145°F with a 3-minute rest time."},
{id:197,cat:"food",q:"Which nutrient deficiency can develop most quickly during an emergency when eating a limited diet?",o:["Iron deficiency, which typically develops over the course of several years of inadequate dietary intake","Calcium deficiency, which causes immediate skeletal deterioration and tooth loss within the first few days","Vitamin C deficiency, which can cause scurvy symptoms in as little as a few weeks","Zinc deficiency, which manifests within hours as severe skin lesions and impaired wound healing","Vitamin A deficiency, which causes total and irreversible blindness overnight without any warning signs"],a:2,src:"CDC",exp:"Vitamin C deficiency can cause symptoms (fatigue, swollen gums, joint pain) in as few as 4-8 weeks without adequate intake. Include citrus, tomatoes, or vitamin C-rich foods in emergency supplies."},
{id:198,cat:"food",q:"How can you cook food without electricity or gas in an emergency?",o:["You cannot cook without utilities; all food must be consumed cold or at room temperature during outages","Put food on a car engine while it runs, using the exhaust manifold heat to slowly warm meals","Microwave food using a standard car battery connected to an inverter, which provides sufficient wattage","Use the dishwasher's residual heat from its last cycle to slowly warm sealed food packages","Outdoor charcoal or propane grill, campfire, solar oven, or canned heat — all with proper ventilation"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Use outdoor grills, campfires, camp stoves, solar ovens, or canned heat. Always use grills and camp stoves outdoors only to prevent carbon monoxide poisoning."},
{id:199,cat:"food",q:"What is the shelf life of commercially available freeze-dried emergency food?",o:["About 1 month before the rehydration quality degrades to the point of being unpalatable and unsafe","Up to 25 to 30 years when properly stored","About 1 year, comparable to most standard canned goods available in grocery stores","About 6 months under ideal conditions, though most manufacturers recommend consuming it much sooner","Indefinite with absolutely no limit, as freeze-drying permanently halts all forms of food degradation"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Properly packaged freeze-dried emergency food can have a shelf life of 25-30 years when stored in cool, dry conditions. The removal of moisture prevents bacterial growth and spoilage."},
{id:200,cat:"food",q:"Why is honey considered an excellent emergency food?",o:["It has no nutritional value whatsoever and is included in emergency kits purely for morale and flavor","It is the only food with complete protein, containing all nine essential amino acids in perfect proportions","It must be refrigerated at all times and will spoil within days if left at room temperature","It has an indefinite shelf life, provides quick energy, and has natural antibacterial properties","It cures all illnesses including bacterial infections, viral diseases, and chronic medical conditions"],a:3,src:"USDA",exp:"Honey never spoils due to its low moisture content and acidic pH. It provides quick energy from simple sugars and has natural antibacterial properties. Do not give to infants under 1 year."},
{id:201,cat:"food",q:"What is the recommended minimum emergency food supply duration for home preparedness?",o:["At least 3 days, with 2 weeks preferred","1 day of shelf-stable provisions","1 month minimum with rotating stock","6 months of freeze-dried and canned goods","1 year of comprehensive food storage supplies"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"FEMA recommends at least a 3-day supply of non-perishable food for evacuation kits and a 2-week supply for sheltering in place at home."},
{id:202,cat:"food",q:"Which common pantry item can be used for both food and water purification?",o:["Granulated white sugar dissolved in solution","Iodized table salt in proper concentrations","Regular unscented household bleach","Baking powder mixed with warm water","Extra-virgin cooking oil"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Unscented household bleach (5-9% sodium hypochlorite) can purify water (8 drops per gallon) and can also be used to sanitize food preparation surfaces and containers."},
{id:203,cat:"food",q:"What should you do with frozen food that has thawed to above 40°F for more than 2 hours?",o:["Refreeze it immediately to restore safe temperatures","Dry it out thoroughly and consume it later","Cook it fully and then refreeze it regardless of type","It remains safe to eat for approximately another full day","Discard it; bacteria may have multiplied"],a:4,src:"USDA",exp:"If food has been above 40°F for more than 2 hours, bacteria may have grown to dangerous levels. The food should be discarded to prevent foodborne illness."},
{id:204,cat:"food",q:"Why should you include a manual can opener in your emergency kit?",o:["To use as a multipurpose prying and cutting tool for various survival applications","Electric openers won't work during a power outage","It is considered a stylish retro preparedness accessory","Manual can openers operate significantly faster than their electric counterparts","For personal self-defense against potential threats in disaster scenarios"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"A manual can opener is essential in emergency kits because canned food is a staple of emergency supplies and electric can openers require power that may not be available."},
{id:205,cat:"food",q:"What is the general rule about eating wild plants you cannot positively identify?",o:["All wild plants found in nature are safe for human consumption","If it has a pleasant smell, it is generally safe to eat","Taste a very small amount and then wait at least one hour for symptoms","Never eat a plant you can't positively identify","Cooking any wild plant at high heat makes it safe to eat"],a:3,src:"USDA",exp:"Many toxic plants resemble edible ones. Never eat a wild plant unless you can positively identify it as safe. Some poisonous plants can cause death even in small amounts."},
{id:206,cat:"food",q:"What is the Universal Edibility Test?",o:["A step-by-step process testing unknown plants from skin contact to small ingestion over 24 hours","Eating everything you find in the wild to systematically build up your tolerance to local plant life","Examining the plant's color, shape, and growing pattern to determine whether it is safe for consumption","Feeding the plant to a small animal first and carefully observing its reaction over several hours","A government-issued food safety certification and labeling program for commercial products"],a:0,src:"USDA",exp:"The Universal Edibility Test involves testing one plant part at a time: contact skin, wait; touch lips, wait; place on tongue, wait; chew without swallowing, wait; eat a small amount and wait 8+ hours. Only use as a last resort."},
{id:207,cat:"food",q:"What are hardtack or pilot bread, and why are they useful for emergencies?",o:["A type of freshly baked artisan bread requiring daily preparation","A commercially produced frozen food product with a short shelf life","Dense crackers of flour, water, and salt that last years","A type of salted and dried jerky made from lean game meat","A specific brand of organic, high-protein granola bar for hikers"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Hardtack and pilot bread are dense, dry crackers with an extremely long shelf life (years to decades) because they contain almost no moisture. They provide calories and carbohydrates."},
{id:208,cat:"food",q:"How can you keep food cold during a power outage without a generator?",o:["Opening the refrigerator frequently to allow cool ambient air to circulate throughout the unit","Wrap the refrigerator tightly in heavy blankets and insulating material to trap residual cold air inside","Put perishable food items outside in direct sun to let natural evaporation cool them","Fan the refrigerator continuously with large pieces of cardboard to promote airflow","Use block ice or frozen water bottles in coolers; keep doors closed"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Transfer the most critical items to coolers with block ice or dry ice (with ventilation). Keep fridge and freezer doors closed — a fridge stays cold about 4 hours if unopened."},
{id:209,cat:"food",q:"At what temperature should a freezer be set for optimal food preservation?",o:["32°F (0°C), the standard freezing point of water","0°F (-18°C) or below","20°F (-7°C), slightly below freezing for energy efficiency","10°F (-12°C), the midpoint between freezing and zero","40°F (4°C), standard refrigerator temperature"],a:1,src:"USDA",exp:"The USDA recommends setting freezers at 0°F (-18°C) or below. At this temperature, bacterial growth is completely stopped, though food quality may still decline over very long periods."},
{id:210,cat:"food",q:"Which of these is NOT a safe method to preserve food without refrigeration?",o:["Canning in a properly calibrated pressure canner following tested recipes","Dehydrating or drying at controlled temperatures with adequate airflow","Salting or curing with measured concentrations of preserving agents","Leaving cooked food at room temperature in a sealed container","Smoking with appropriate wood at sustained temperatures over several hours"],a:3,src:"USDA",exp:"Leaving cooked food at room temperature, even in a sealed container, allows bacterial growth. Safe preservation methods include canning, dehydrating, salting, curing, smoking, and pickling."},
{id:211,cat:"food",q:"How many gallons of water should you store per person per day for food preparation in addition to drinking water?",o:["At least half a gallon for food prep and hygiene","None; food preparation does not require any extra water beyond what you drink","5 gallons per person per day for all cooking, cleaning, and sanitation needs","10 gallons per person per day to cover comprehensive food preparation and cleanup","One cup total, just enough to reconstitute basic freeze-dried meals"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"The 1 gallon per person per day recommendation from FEMA includes both drinking and basic sanitation/food prep. Cooking reconstituted foods (rice, pasta) requires additional water."},
{id:212,cat:"food",q:"What is the main danger of improperly home-canned food?",o:["It develops an unpleasant taste and unappetizing texture over time","It gradually changes color and becomes visually unappealing","Botulism from Clostridium botulinum toxin","It becomes excessively salty and dehydrated during the canning process","It shrinks significantly in size and loses nearly all nutritional value"],a:2,src:"USDA",exp:"Botulism from Clostridium botulinum can occur in improperly canned low-acid foods. The toxin is odorless and tasteless but can be fatal. Use tested USDA recipes and pressure canning for low-acid foods."},
{id:213,cat:"food",q:"What signs indicate that home-canned food may have botulism contamination?",o:["Clear liquid with no particles and a firm, properly seated seal","A tight vacuum seal with no visible air bubbles inside the jar","Perfectly intact and undamaged labels with clear manufacturing dates","Normal, expected food color consistent with the original product","Bulging lids, broken seals, spurting liquid, or off-odors"],a:4,src:"USDA",exp:"Warning signs include bulging lids, broken seals, leaking, spurting liquid when opened, off-odors, cloudiness, and mold. Never taste suspicious canned food — discard it safely."},
{id:214,cat:"food",q:"What special dietary needs should be considered in emergency food planning?",o:["No special dietary needs exist during emergencies since survival overrides all restrictions","Allergies, infant formula, diabetes management, and medications requiring food","Only total calorie count matters when planning emergency food provisions","Only personal taste preferences and flavor variety for maintaining morale","Only provisions for adults since children can eat whatever is available"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Plan for food allergies, infant needs (formula, baby food), medical diets (diabetes, celiac), elderly needs (soft foods), and medications that must be taken with food."},
{id:215,cat:"food",q:"How long does powdered milk last when stored properly in a sealed container?",o:["About 1 week before it begins to clump and lose nutritional value","Exactly 1 year regardless of storage conditions or container type","About 1 month when kept in a cool, dry pantry environment","Up to 20-25 years for nonfat varieties in sealed, oxygen-free containers","It cannot be stored for any meaningful length of time safely"],a:3,src:"USDA",exp:"Nonfat dried milk stored in sealed, oxygen-free containers (such as #10 cans with oxygen absorbers) in cool temperatures can last 20-25 years. Once opened, use within a few months."},
{id:216,cat:"food",q:"What is the 'sniff test' for food safety, and is it reliable?",o:["Smelling food to check freshness; it is NOT reliable since many bacteria produce no odor","Smelling food to determine if it is safe; it is a completely reliable method endorsed by all major food safety organizations worldwide","It is a clinical medical diagnostic test specifically designed for identifying food allergies","It only applies to dairy products such as milk, yogurt, cheese, and cream-based items","It involves testing food samples with specialized chemical indicator strips for contamination"],a:0,src:"USDA",exp:"While obviously spoiled food often smells bad, many dangerous pathogens (like Salmonella and E. coli) produce no odor, taste, or visible changes. The sniff test alone is not reliable for food safety."},
{id:217,cat:"food",q:"What is the benefit of including electrolyte replacement drinks or packets in emergency supplies?",o:["They have a pleasant taste that boosts morale during stressful emergency situations","They contain caffeine and other stimulants that provide sustained energy boosts","They replace electrolytes lost through sweating, vomiting, or diarrhea","They chemically purify water and make it safe for drinking in the field","They serve as a complete nutritional meal replacement eliminating the need for solid food"],a:2,src:"CDC",exp:"Electrolyte solutions replace critical minerals (sodium, potassium, chloride) lost through sweating, illness, or exertion. Electrolyte imbalances can cause muscle cramps, confusion, and cardiac problems."},
{id:218,cat:"food",q:"How should you handle a propane grill when cooking during an emergency?",o:["Use it indoors in the kitchen with the range hood fan running on high","Use it inside the garage with the door cracked open at least six inches for ventilation","Store propane tanks inside the house in a closet away from direct heat sources","Use it anywhere indoors as long as windows and exterior doors are fully open","Use outdoors only, away from structures, checking for leaks first"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Propane grills must be used outdoors only, at least 10 feet from structures. Check connections for gas leaks with soapy water. Never store propane tanks indoors."},
{id:219,cat:"food",q:"What is food-grade diatomaceous earth used for in food storage?",o:["As a mineral-rich seasoning to enhance flavor in survival cooking","Mixed into dry grains and beans to prevent insect infestation","As a natural food coloring agent derived from fossilized algae deposits","To significantly increase the caloric density of stored bulk food items","To add essential moisture back into over-dried foods during long-term storage"],a:1,src:"USDA",exp:"Food-grade diatomaceous earth can be mixed with dry bulk foods to prevent insect infestation. It works by damaging insects' exoskeletons. Use only food-grade, not pool-grade diatomaceous earth."},
{id:220,cat:"food",q:"What is the recommended way to heat an MRE using its included flameless ration heater?",o:["Microwave the entire sealed package on high power for approximately three minutes","Submerge the entire MRE completely in a pot of rapidly boiling water for ten minutes","Light the chemical heater bag on fire with a match and place the entree on top","Add water to the heater bag, insert the entree, and lean it against an object","Place the sealed package in direct sunlight for approximately 4 hours to warm gradually"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Add about 1 ounce of water to the flameless ration heater bag, insert the entree pouch, fold the top, and lean it against an object (rock it back). The chemical reaction generates heat in about 10-12 minutes."},
{id:221,cat:"comms",q:"What is the universal emergency phone number in the United States?",o:["911","311 for non-emergency municipal services","411 for directory assistance and information","999 which is used in the United Kingdom","112 which is the European standard emergency number"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"911 is the universal emergency number in the United States for police, fire, and medical emergencies. It works from all phones, including cell phones without an active plan."},
{id:222,cat:"comms",q:"What emergency number works on GSM cell phones in most countries worldwide?",o:["911 only, which has been adopted as the global standard","999, the traditional British emergency telephone number","112","000, the Australian national emergency telephone number","555, a universally reserved telecommunications number"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"112 is the international emergency number that works on GSM networks in most countries. Many countries also accept 911. Your phone may route to local emergency services automatically."},
{id:223,cat:"comms",q:"Why are text messages often more reliable than voice calls during a disaster?",o:["They utilize significantly more network bandwidth allowing priority routing through congested systems","Voice calls never work under any circumstances during an emergency event","They are always delivered faster than voice calls regardless of network conditions","They use military-grade end-to-end encryption that gets network priority","They use less bandwidth and can send even when voice networks are congested"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Text messages require much less network bandwidth than voice calls and can queue and send when brief network capacity becomes available, making them more reliable during network congestion."},
{id:224,cat:"comms",q:"What is the NOAA Weather Radio frequency band?",o:["The standard AM radio broadcast band between 540 and 1700 kHz","The 162.400 to 162.550 MHz band","The standard FM radio broadcast band between 88.1 and 107.9 MHz","International shortwave radio frequencies only, requiring specialized antenna equipment","The SiriusXM satellite radio proprietary digital broadcast band"],a:1,src:"NOAA",exp:"NOAA Weather Radio broadcasts continuous weather information on seven frequencies in the 162.400 to 162.550 MHz band, requiring a special weather radio or scanner to receive."},
{id:225,cat:"comms",q:"What does the Emergency Alert System (EAS) do?",o:["Provides entertainment programming and music during extended emergency situations","It is a private encrypted messaging system exclusively for government officials","It only handles weather-related emergencies such as tornados, hurricanes, and severe storms","It lets officials broadcast emergency alerts to the public via radio, TV, and cable","It only works on the internet through web browsers and dedicated mobile applications"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"The EAS is a national public warning system that enables the President and authorized federal, state, and local officials to broadcast emergency alerts through radio, TV, and cable."},
{id:226,cat:"comms",q:"What is Wireless Emergency Alerts (WEA)?",o:["A system sending targeted alerts to cell phones in affected areas without sign-up","A premium subscription-based weather forecasting and notification service","A social media platform specifically designed for sharing real-time emergency information","A specialized app you must download and configure from your phone's app store","A dedicated landline phone service for receiving automated emergency notifications"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"WEA sends geographically targeted emergency alerts (extreme weather, AMBER alerts, presidential alerts) directly to compatible cell phones in the affected area. No subscription needed."},
{id:227,cat:"comms",q:"What is the international distress signal using sound or light?",o:["Two short signals repeated continuously at regular five-second intervals","Five long signals followed by a one-minute pause between repetitions","Three evenly spaced signals of any kind, repeated at intervals","One continuous unbroken signal maintained for as long as physically possible","Seven short signals in rapid succession followed by a thirty-second pause"],a:2,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Three signals of any type (whistle blasts, gunshots, fires, flashes of light) spaced evenly and repeated at regular intervals is the internationally recognized distress signal."},
{id:228,cat:"comms",q:"What does SOS stand for in Morse code, and how is it transmitted?",o:["Save Our Ship, transmitted as three long dashes with brief pauses between each one","Start Over Soon, transmitted as two short beeps followed by a long pause","Stop Our Signal, transmitted as five short beeps in rapid succession","Send Our Saviors, transmitted as one extended long dash lasting several seconds","It stands for nothing specific; transmitted as three short, three long, three short signals"],a:4,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"SOS is an international distress signal chosen for its simplicity in Morse code: three dots, three dashes, three dots (· · · — — — · · ·). It does not officially stand for any phrase."},
{id:229,cat:"comms",q:"What type of radio does not require a license to operate and is useful for short-range emergency communication?",o:["Amateur (Ham) radio, which provides extensive long-range communication capabilities","FRS (Family Radio Service) radios","International shortwave radio receivers and transceivers for global communications","CB radio, which requires a current FCC-issued station license to legally operate","Military-specification tactical radio systems designed for field deployment"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"FRS (Family Radio Service) radios do not require a license, are inexpensive, and provide short-range (1-2 miles) two-way communication, making them ideal for family emergency communication."},
{id:230,cat:"comms",q:"What is the typical range of FRS (Family Radio Service) radios in realistic conditions?",o:["100+ miles with a clear line of sight from an elevated position","About 25 miles under average suburban conditions with standard antennas","About 50 miles in flat, open terrain with no significant obstructions","About 0.5 to 2 miles in typical conditions","Unlimited range when atmospheric conditions are favorable for signal propagation"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Despite manufacturer claims of longer ranges, FRS radios typically reach 0.5 to 2 miles in realistic conditions with buildings, trees, and terrain. Line of sight improves range significantly."},
{id:231,cat:"comms",q:"What is a HAM (Amateur) radio, and why is it valuable in emergencies?",o:["A licensed radio service for long-distance communication independent of phone and internet","A battery-powered toy walkie-talkie primarily designed for children's recreational use","A commercial broadcast radio station that transmits emergency programming to listeners","A satellite phone system requiring a monthly subscription and specialized data plan","A specific type of CB radio with slightly enhanced range and additional channel options"],a:0,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Amateur (HAM) radio can communicate locally and worldwide without relying on cellular, internet, or telephone infrastructure. It requires an FCC license but is invaluable when other systems fail."},
{id:232,cat:"comms",q:"What is ARES (Amateur Radio Emergency Service)?",o:["A commercial emergency service provider offering professional first-responder communications support","A government-operated satellite network used exclusively by federal emergency management agencies","Licensed amateur radio operators organized for emergency communications","An internet-based emergency discussion forum for sharing real-time situational awareness reports","A brand of portable emergency radio equipment manufactured for consumer preparedness kits"],a:2,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"ARES is an ARRL-organized group of licensed amateur radio volunteers who provide emergency and public service communications during disasters when normal communications fail."},
{id:233,cat:"comms",q:"What is the best way to conserve cell phone battery during an emergency?",o:["Keep all apps actively running in the background to receive real-time updates and notifications","Make continuous calls every few minutes to repeatedly check whether cellular service has been restored","Charge the phone by placing it inside a standard household microwave oven for thirty seconds","Keep the phone in direct sunlight since photovoltaic cells in the screen will recharge the battery","Reduce brightness, disable Bluetooth and WiFi, close apps, use airplane mode between calls"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Conserve battery by reducing brightness, closing apps, disabling Bluetooth/WiFi/location services, using airplane mode between use, and keeping the phone warm (cold drains batteries faster)."},
{id:234,cat:"comms",q:"What should be included in a family emergency communication plan?",o:["Only the home street address written on a piece of paper for each family member","Out-of-area contact, meeting locations, emergency numbers, and family contact info","Only the parents' personal cell phone numbers stored in each child's phone","Just the 911 number since dispatchers can coordinate all other necessary communications","Only the school's main office phone number and the children's classroom extensions"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"FEMA recommends designating an out-of-area contact (long-distance calls often work when local ones don't), two meeting places, and a wallet card with all important numbers for each family member."},
{id:235,cat:"comms",q:"Why is an out-of-area emergency contact important in a family communication plan?",o:["They can wire money and provide immediate financial assistance to displaced family members","They are statistically always available to answer calls regardless of time of day or circumstances","They consistently have stronger cell phone coverage and higher-quality network connections","Long-distance lines may work when local ones are jammed; they serve as a relay point","They can physically travel to the disaster area and provide hands-on assistance more quickly"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"During local disasters, local phone networks are often overwhelmed. Calls to distant areas may get through, allowing an out-of-area contact to relay messages between separated family members."},
{id:236,cat:"comms",q:"What is a ground-to-air signal panel?",o:["A bright material laid on open ground to signal aircraft","A portable high-frequency radio transmitter designed specifically for contacting overflying aircraft","A type of handheld pyrotechnic flare launched vertically to attract the attention of search planes","A specialized signal mirror with built-in compass for directing reflected light at aircraft","A downloadable cell phone app that flashes the screen in internationally recognized distress patterns"],a:0,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Ground-to-air signal panels are large, high-visibility materials placed in clearings to attract attention from search aircraft. Use bright or contrasting colors and make signals at least 10 feet across."},
{id:237,cat:"comms",q:"How can a signal mirror be used effectively for rescue?",o:["Only at night when the reflected light creates maximum visible contrast against the dark sky","Hold it directly above your head and shake it vigorously in all directions","Aim reflected sunlight toward rescuers by sighting through the mirror's hole","Point the reflected light at the ground in a circular pattern to create a visible landing zone","It only works effectively in completely overcast weather when diffused light enhances reflection"],a:2,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"A signal mirror can flash sunlight up to 100 miles on a clear day. Sight through the aiming hole, catch the sun's reflection, and sweep it across the target aircraft or vessel."},
{id:238,cat:"comms",q:"What does the acronym CERT stand for?",o:["Central Emergency Radio Team coordinating regional broadcast communications","County Emergency Relay Terminal for routing inter-agency disaster messages","Critical Event Recovery Taskforce specializing in post-disaster infrastructure restoration","City Emergency Rescue Technicians providing professional urban search operations","Community Emergency Response Team"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"CERT (Community Emergency Response Team) is a FEMA program that trains civilians in basic disaster response skills including fire safety, light search and rescue, and emergency communications."},
{id:239,cat:"comms",q:"What information should you provide when calling 911?",o:["Only your first and last name so they can look up your address in their database","Location, nature of emergency, number of people, victim conditions, and hazards","Only what you think may have happened based on your initial assessment of the situation","Just ask them to come quickly without wasting time providing any further details","Your phone number only so the dispatcher can call you back for a more detailed interview"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Provide your exact location, the nature of the emergency, how many people need help, the condition of victims, and any immediate hazards. Stay on the line until the dispatcher says you can hang up."},
{id:240,cat:"comms",q:"What is a Personal Locator Beacon (PLB)?",o:["A specialized cell phone app that uses standard cellular data to transmit your GPS coordinates","A handheld portable two-way radio with extended range capabilities for backcountry communication","A high-intensity waterproof flashlight with built-in strobe mode for nighttime signaling","A device that sends a satellite distress signal to alert search and rescue","A dedicated GPS navigation device used only for route planning and waypoint tracking"],a:3,src:"NOAA",exp:"A PLB is a small, portable device that when activated transmits a distress signal on 406 MHz via satellite to the global COSPAS-SARSAT search and rescue system, providing your GPS coordinates."},
{id:241,cat:"comms",q:"What frequency does the COSPAS-SARSAT satellite system monitor for distress signals?",o:["406 MHz","FM 100.1 MHz, a standard commercial broadcast frequency","AM 530 kHz, the lowest frequency on the AM broadcast dial","900 MHz, commonly used by cordless telephones and consumer electronics","2.4 GHz, the standard WiFi and Bluetooth communication frequency band"],a:0,src:"NOAA",exp:"The international COSPAS-SARSAT satellite system monitors 406 MHz for distress signals from EPIRBs, ELTs, and PLBs. This frequency provides global coverage and rapid location determination."},
{id:242,cat:"comms",q:"How can you signal for help using a whistle?",o:["One single long sustained blow lasting approximately thirty seconds","Continuous uninterrupted blowing without stopping until someone responds to the sound","Three short blasts repeated at regular intervals","Two quick blasts followed by a ten-second pause, then repeated continuously","Random alternating patterns of short and long blows to attract maximum attention"],a:2,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"Three short whistle blasts repeated at intervals is the international distress signal. A whistle carries much farther than a human voice and requires less energy to use."},
{id:243,cat:"comms",q:"What is the advantage of a hand-crank or solar-powered emergency radio?",o:["It produces significantly better sound quality than battery-powered models due to its generator design","It can both receive and transmit two-way emergency messages to nearby stations","It receives a substantially wider range of channels including international shortwave broadcasts","It is fully waterproof and submersible, making it ideal for flood and maritime emergencies","It works without batteries or external power, ensuring access to emergency broadcasts"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Hand-crank and solar radios can operate indefinitely without batteries or external power. They ensure you can receive NOAA weather alerts and emergency broadcasts during extended power outages."},
{id:244,cat:"comms",q:"What is the standard CB (Citizens Band) radio emergency channel?",o:["Channel 1, the first and lowest frequency in the Citizens Band radio allocation","Channel 9","Channel 19, primarily used by long-haul truckers for traffic and road conditions","Channel 40, the highest frequency channel available on standard CB radio sets","Channel 14, designated for interdepartmental government emergency coordination"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Channel 9 is the designated emergency and traveler assistance channel on CB radio. Channel 19 is commonly used by truckers for general communication and traffic information."},
{id:245,cat:"comms",q:"What visual distress signals are required for recreational boats in US coastal waters?",o:["None are required under current United States Coast Guard maritime safety regulations","A fully charged cell phone with waterproof case is considered legally sufficient","Only a plain white flag displayed prominently from the vessel's highest accessible point","USCG-approved signals such as flares or an orange flag and electric light","Only a waterproof flashlight capable of producing a sustained visible beam at night"],a:3,src:"NOAA",exp:"USCG regulations require recreational boats in coastal waters to carry approved visual distress signals: pyrotechnic devices (flares) for day and night use, or a combination of orange flag (day) and electric SOS light (night)."},
{id:246,cat:"comms",q:"What does the phrase 'Mayday' signify in emergency communications?",o:["The most serious distress call, indicating grave and imminent danger","A general radio greeting used to establish initial contact between stations","A specialized coded weather forecast transmitted to maritime and aviation receivers","A routine radio check performed daily to verify equipment is functioning properly","A minor equipment problem requiring non-urgent maintenance or technical assistance"],a:0,src:"NOAA",exp:"Mayday (from French 'm'aider' — help me) is the highest-priority distress call indicating that a person, vessel, or aircraft is in grave and imminent danger and requires immediate assistance."},
{id:247,cat:"comms",q:"How many times should 'Mayday' be repeated at the start of a distress call?",o:["Once, spoken clearly and deliberately","Twice, with a brief pause between each repetition","Three times: 'Mayday, Mayday, Mayday'","Five times to ensure the message is clearly received by all monitoring stations","Ten times in rapid succession before providing any additional identifying information"],a:2,src:"NOAA",exp:"The proper format begins with 'Mayday, Mayday, Mayday,' followed by 'This is [vessel/aircraft name]' repeated three times, then your position, nature of distress, and assistance needed."},
{id:248,cat:"comms",q:"What technology allows modern smartphones to send emergency SOS messages via satellite when there is no cell service?",o:["Standard WiFi calling protocols that automatically reroute through any available wireless network","NFC (Near Field Communication) chips that bounce distress signals between nearby compatible devices","Bluetooth long-range mode that extends signal range to reach the nearest cellular tower","Standard SMS text messaging which uses minimal bandwidth to penetrate weak signal areas","Satellite SOS features built into newer smartphones"],a:4,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"Some modern smartphones include satellite communication capabilities that allow users to send emergency SOS messages and share their location with rescue services when outside cellular coverage."},
{id:249,cat:"comms",q:"What information should be included on a family emergency wallet card?",o:["Only your home address and the names of everyone who lives at that residence","Emergency contacts, meeting places, medical info, allergies, and insurance details","Only your first and last name along with a recent photograph for identification","Just a current family photo so first responders can identify and reunite separated members","Only your primary care doctor's office phone number and their after-hours answering service"],a:1,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"A wallet card should include emergency contacts, the out-of-area relay contact, two meeting locations, medical conditions, allergies, medications, blood type, and insurance/policy numbers."},
{id:250,cat:"comms",q:"What is the 'two-way communication' rule in emergency preparedness?",o:["Always carry two fully charged phones with different cellular service providers","Send every important message twice using the same communication method for confirmation","Talk to at least two different people about every emergency situation for verification","Have at least two independent methods of receiving and sending emergency information","Only communicate in pairs so that one person can verify what the other person heard"],a:3,src:"FEMA/Ready.gov",exp:"FEMA recommends having multiple independent communication methods (cell phone, NOAA radio, FRS radios, etc.) because any single system can fail during a disaster. Redundancy is critical."},
{id:251,cat:"first-aid",q:"Identify the body position shown in this image. When should it be used?",o:["The Trendelenburg position, used to treat low blood pressure","The recovery position, used for unconscious but breathing victims","The shock position, used when a patient is in hypovolemic shock","The prone position, used during CPR to clear the airway","The lateral recumbent position, used only for spinal injury patients"],a:1,src:"American Red Cross",exp:"The recovery position (lateral recumbent) keeps the airway clear and allows fluids to drain from the mouth. It is used for unconscious victims who are breathing normally and have no suspected spinal injury.",media:{type:"image",url:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Recovery_position.svg/512px-Recovery_position.svg.png",alt:"Person lying in the recovery position on their side",caption:"Image: Recovery position (public domain, Wikimedia Commons)"}},
{id:252,cat:"water",q:"What does this image show, and why is it an important wilderness survival technique?",o:["A rain barrel collection system for long-term water storage","A solar still used to extract drinkable water from the ground","A fish trap designed for shallow stream environments","A ground-level fire pit covered for overnight heat retention","A pit latrine setup following backcountry sanitation guidelines"],a:1,src:"US Army Survival Manual FM 21-76",exp:"A solar still uses a sheet of clear plastic over a hole in the ground. The sun evaporates moisture from the soil, which condenses on the plastic and drips into a collection container — producing clean drinking water.",media:{type:"image",url:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/41/Solar_still_diagram.svg/512px-Solar_still_diagram.svg.png",alt:"Diagram of a solar still for water collection",caption:"Diagram: Solar still (public domain, Wikimedia Commons)"}}
];
